<HEADLINE>
FT  24 MAR 92 / The FT Review of Business Books (28): Walking back to
happiness
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JDF JONES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE MAN WHO BROKE OUT OF THE BANK . . . by Miles Morland Bloomsbury Pounds
16.99, 216 pages
HERE IS my early (and not-too-serious) nomination for the best, by which I
mean the most enjoyable, 'Business Book' of 1992.
That may seem surprising, as it is not exactly an endorsement of the
challenges and satisfactions of the life of the international financier: on
the contrary, it is irresistible case for the wisdom of giving it all up.
Miles Morland had spent, as he puts it, 'Twenty-Two Years Shouting Down A
Phone'. After nine years on Wall Street he ran First Boston's brokerage
office in London. At 45 he was - well, not quite bored, but he knew he had
stopped learning. So he quit, and went off with his wife to walk across
France.
This is the story of The Walk, though the brief sequences in the City -
Rudloff, Von Klemm, etc - are fascinating (and funny) enough to make one
wish he would write at length about these things. (Says his 'rabbi' Luis in
New York when told of his resignation: 'You're not gonna work for those
fockers at Solly, are you?'. Before the Walk was over, Luis had quit too.)
'Non-City people think the satisfaction is in the money,' Morland says of
his professional life. 'They're wrong. Most of the pleasure comes from the
sheer competitive intensity of the work. But when I became successful in the
City, I had the same feeling I had had at Oxford or Radley as a successful
sportsman. I was wearing a suit that looked good, but hadn't it been made
for someone else?'
So at 45 he called a halt. 'Everyone else was secretly longing to do it
too.'
It is 350 miles from Mediterranean to Atlantic (Narbonne, Carcassonne, etc)
and Morland writes of provincial France better, more convincingly, less
sentimentally, than Peter Mayle. Having a half-French wife helps.
The hotels are more often grotty than charming, the natives are frequently
rude, the dogs are terrifying. Blisters, tendons, boots, showers, figure
prominently for this out-of-condition couple; ants, wasps and cockroaches
seem to feature on every page, as do many, many enthusiastically described
meals of (sometimes) wonderful food washed down with many a bottle.
It is agony and ecstasy in a mid-life crisis, set candidly in the context of
a marriage with a tricky past - they had divorced and remarried when he was
at the height of his career. Best of all, it is extremely funny, and the fun
never flags until they are paddling in the Atlantic. I foretell a rash of
resignations in EC2 in coming weeks.
'Do you miss it?' Guislaine asked.
'What do you think?'
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page XII
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT921-1596</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CCXBBAA0FT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920324
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  24 MAR 92 / The FT Review of Business Books (26): Wolfe in sheep's
clothing
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NIGEL ANDREWS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE DEVIL'S CANDY by Julie Salamon Jonathan Cape Pounds 15.99, 423 pages
The Devil's Candy is subtitled The Bonfire Of The Vanities Goes To
Hollywood. Most famous novels that go to Hollywood never come back: or not
until they have been made into a glossy meld of stardust and hype in which
you need not bother to look for traces of the real Dostoevsky, Conrad or
Hemingway.
Tom Wolfe is none of these. But The Bonfire Of The Vanities, if not a great
novel, is a strongly defined one. The flames of its social and racial satire
are non-discriminating: they crackle through New York from the Bronx to the
Battery, pausing longest in Wall Street where they climb tall buildings to
find their stockbroker hero, Sherman McCoy, and pull him down like a burning
Icarus.
The cardinal crime of Brian De Palma's film of the novel, which on reaching
the screen crashed even more spectacularly than its hero (less Icarus, more
the Hindenburg), was to soften the original's ferocity. As Wall Street
Journal film critic Julie Salamon tells us in her engrossing story of the
production, Warner Brothers spent Dollars 50m dressing Wolfe in sheep's
clothing.
Yes, there is some generic, half-witted satire in Bruce Willis's picture of
the drunken, originally English tabloid reporter, Fallow. Yes, the
rabble-rousing black leader Reverend Bacon is allowed to sizzle a little
under De Palma's wide-angle lenses. But all that most filmgoers remember are
the over-lavish production values, the game but miscast Tom Hanks, and the
risible attempt at racial even-handedness in the transformation of the
novel's goodhearted deus ex machina Judge Kovitsky (Jewish) into the movie's
Judge White (black).
The heart-searching that produced this decision is one of the high points of
Salamon's chronicle. When Morgan Freeman stepped into the Judge's role to
deliver the cringe-making final speech fashioned by scriptwriter Michael
Cristofer - 'Decency is what your mother taught you' etc - The Bonfire Of
The Vanities finally consumed itself. Its flames, unlike the caustic ones
created by Wolfe, were the self-devouring ones of box-office opportunism.
Salamon's book may become a classic because its author, in addition to
writing well, has happened on a classic case history. Neither she nor the
film's makers could have foreseen that Bonfire would attract all the
night-flying, fabric-eating, spendthrift idiocies modern Hollywood is
capable of.
Hundreds of thousands of dollars were spent combing the North-Eastern states
to find the 'right' courtroom for Morgan Freeman. (Couldn't they have built
one?) More six- and seven-figure sums were spent on showy establishing
shots, like Concorde landing in a line with the setting sun; on providing
human support systems for 'difficult' stars such as Melanie Griffith; and on
 -but the list is as long, loud and unappeasable as Sherman McCoy's
dachsund.
Canine similes seem apt in a production which illuminates the besetting vice
of modern Hollywood. In thrall to the pseudoscience of audience market
research, the industry allows the tail to wag the dog.
For studios the far-off imaginary twitches of filmgoer response dictate the
choreographing of the movie's own gestures and movements in production.
Given the responsibility of a big-budget film on which he was shadowed by
Warner executives at every step, even a film-maker like Brian De Palma
succumbs to the prognosticatory anxiety. Indeed it was De Palma, Salomon
tells us, who cast Morgan Freeman as the Judge. Aim: to sweeten the film's
eventual appeal to black and liberal filmgoers.
Nothing is more quietly horrific in Julie Salamon's book than the final
fever of sneak previews. A film that might once have had a unified vision,
back when De Palma first read the novel, is shredded and re-edited in the
weeks before its Christmas 1990 release on the say-so of a few thousand
preview cards. The monosyllabic 'liked' and 'didn't like' verdicts of
moviegoers in middle Texas or outer Wyoming are allowed to reshape an entire
film.
One cannot make good art like this; one cannot even be sure of making good
entertainment. But Warners will no doubt have learned this itself after its
Bonfire finger-burning. As Salamon mischievously notes, a month before De
Palma's folie de grandeur opened, a low-budget, low-expectation comedy
called Home Alone opened in America and began its climb to become the third
most successful film in history. It was produced by 20th Century Fox after
Warner Bros, its initial producers, passed on the project.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page XII
