<HEADLINE>
FT  24 MAR 92 / The FT Review of Business Books (25): Decisions, decisions,
decisions
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PRABHU GUPTARA
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
WHAT consequences will the Single European Market have for business? It will
change the world, say the believers. Nonsense, retort the sceptics, the
Single Market will have no substantial consequences at all. Which opinion
should you trust?
Do not trust either. Examine your own situation and decide for yourself. The
answer depends on several factors: the size of your company, the
geographical area, the industrial or commercial sector, your time horizon,
and so on. To make all this simpler, Ceres and Durham University Business
School have produced the peculiarly-named EuroTrain (ring-bound, A4, two
volumes, approx 130 pages, Pounds 70) which sets out to be a tool-kit for
developing your own European strategy.
EuroTrain aspires to integrate all the details of the various Single Market
measures into a single, logical format so that their impact on a particular
business can be evaluated systematically and comprehensively. At least, that
is the aim of the first volume; the points in it which are blindingly
obvious to me are probably not quite so obvious to others, and vice versa,
no doubt. In any case, publishers are more likely to go wrong by skipping
what seems obvious than they are by including some matters which may appear
elementary.
The second volume provides names and addresses of all the organisations
which are mentioned in the first volume. The value of this is somewhat
dubious, partly because several of the organisations listed would be unable
to provide you with anything particularly enlightening, and partly because
several organisations which could provide relevant information are excluded.
But, even by itself, Volume 1 is good value for money if it is going to help
you decide on a matter as important as your European strategy.
                           *       *      *
Wouldn't it be lovely if we could entrust all of life's little decisions to
a computer? We are not quite there yet, but there are a growing number of
software packages which help simplify, segment and clarify, decision-making.
The latest of these is Strad, specifically designed for the PC. Planning in
the face of multiple uncertainty, under the pressure of fast-moving events,
calls for a particular kind of cool thinking, a special kind of
rational-cum-insightful analysis, which can be helped by the way in which
computers handle issues.
Strad sees the central challenges as managing of the different sources of
uncertainty and balancing commitment in the short term with flexibility in
the future.
The instructions which come with the software are sometimes a little
difficult to follow, and the ins and outs of the system force one to think
quite carefully about the problem in hand. But, once mastered, the system
makes decisions markedly less fraught and more thoroughly considered.
                           *       *      *
Precisely what makes decision-making fraught - that is, the rapidity and
complexity of change - is what makes organisational renewal so necessary.
Rosabeth Moss Kanter has made her name as a management guru specialising in
the management of change, and some of her latest thinking is captured in The
Great Balancing Act (BBC Training Videos, set of two videos, with Training
Notes, Pounds 299 plus VAT).
The average life-span of an organisation - 40 years - is less than the
average life-span of a human being, and Kanter basic message is that, if
organisations wish to survive, they need to become faster, more focused,
more flexible and more friendly.
One of the factors which can make an organisation quicker is a move away
from the traditional job description-ruled hierarchy to flatter,
project-oriented teams which form and re-form as need arises or passes.
This calls for transformation, not just of structures but more crucially of
the mentality of individuals.
While hierarchical management is control-orientation project leadership is
oriented towards liberation, teamwork and shared achievement.
To assist with this individual transformation, you may wish to try Daedal's
The Project, another of its paper maze-exercises (ring-bound, A4, with OHP
masters, and handout masters, Pounds 125) which is designed to help people,
up to middle management levels, to succeed as project leaders.
Unfortunately, there is little aimed at more senior people even though
businesses can only grow to the level of their chief executives, and unless
these executives keep learning there is little chance for the organisation
to keep growing.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page XI
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT921-1599</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CCXBBAAXFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920324
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  24 MAR 92 / The FT Review of Business Books (24): What makes a self-made
man - The search for the secret of entrepreneurial success
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHARLES BATCHELOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
JUST AS the alchemists in the Middle Ages sought for the formula for turning
base metal into gold, so researchers in more recent times have attempted to
distil the essence of the entrepreneur.
What is it that distinguishes the self-made man from his counterpart who is
quite happy to spend his working life in the employ of others? What prompts
some managers to leave well-paid jobs in large corporations to set up in
business on their own or to stage a management buy-out?
The business tycoon has always fascinated readers, as the newspaper column
inches and the yards of bookshelf devoted to men such as Robert Maxwell,
'Tiny' Rowland and Richard Branson testify. But the past decade and a half
has seen a more serious interest develop as the important economic role of
small businesses - and the men and women who run them - has become better
appreciated. If we can understand what makes the entrepreneur tick,
governments may be able to devise policies to encourage enterprise.
Four recent books each examine different aspects of the entrepreneurial
psyche and the world in which entrepreneurs operate. For the policy-maker
there is a discouraging inconclusiveness to their findings.
Entrepreneur] by Tom Lloyd (Bloomsbury Pounds 9.99, 176 pages) promises
insights into the entrepreneurial mind but fails to deliver. Lloyd takes the
life stories of eight entrepreneurs as the basis for his book but then
perversely chops them into sections which fit his chapter headings,
weakening the narrative effect.
Some of the entrepreneurs chosen, such as Bob Payton, the pizza potentate,
and global marketeer Martin Sorrell, will be familiar to many readers but
Lloyd does the debate a service by broadening his definition to include
Jenny Pitman, a leading racehorse trainer, and Richard Noble, holder of the
world land speed record.
Puzzlingly, the author says his aim is to tell us about the entrepreneur as
a 'human being living in the ordinary world', though most of us want to know
what makes entrepreneurs different. On this score the book is disappointing.
It points to the entrepreneur as having a positive outlook, a different
vision system and a love of change. Newcomers to the subject of enterprise
may find Entrepreneur] a readable basic introduction but must look for more
probing approach elsewhere.
The Naked Entrepreneur (Kogan Page Pounds 14.95/Pounds 7.99, 122 pages)
attempts a more substantial analysis and seeks to paint a picture of the
entrepreneur stripped of what the author, David Robinson, calls 'the
self-seeking promotion of the gossip columns.'
But Robinson's conclusion that the entrepreneur is 'dedicated to the pursuit
of wealth and power' differs from that of many other studies which have
stressed that money is not a prime motivator. His study also suffers from a
lack of real case histories. He draws on his experience as an accountant for
his analysis but, being unwilling to use identifiable examples of clients,
opts for 'composites' of real people he has known to illustrate his
arguments.
Like so many other studies of the entrepreneur this one notes that much of
the evidence on the motivation of entrepreneurs is conflicting, but
concludes they possess in accentuated form common character traits such as
imagination and dedication.
One advantage of creating 'composite' entrepreneurs is that the author
avoids any sexual bias, but most books devoted to enterprise suggest it is a
largely male activity. However, as Women as Entrepreneurs (Academic Press
Pounds 24.95, 172 pages) points out, male self-employment rose by only 30
per cent in Britain during the 1980s while female self-employment rose 70
per cent. This soberly academic book by Sara Carter and Tom Cannon studies
the problems confronting this largely unacknowledged army of women
entrepreneurs.
It examines the proposition that women face problems, some of which are in
addition to, or different from, those met by men in starting up and running
a business. In spite of the detail of the argument the reader is left with
the feeling that the similarities are greater than the differences.
The Carter/Cannon study identifies five types of female entrepreneur ranging
from the youngish, frustrated career woman to the older returner who has
raised a family. The successful ones have in common a high degree of formal
education and a willingness to train to fill the gaps in their business
skills. In contrast to Robinson's conclusion that money is an important
motivator, Carter and Cannon find women judge success in personal rather
than commercial terms, at least in the early stages of their entrepreneurial
careers.
Entrepreneurs in High Technology (Oxford-New York Dollars 27.95, 386 pages)
looks at a very different sample of entrepreneurs but comes to remarkably
similar conclusions about motivation.
Most company founders are strongly driven by a desire for independence but
are only moderately interested in financial rewards when they start, says
Edward B. Roberts, professor of technology management at the Massachusetts
Institute of Technology (MIT).
Roberts' entrepreneurs form an elite group, largely comprising former
students and academics from MIT who set up business in the technological
hot-house formed by companies on Boston's Route 128. For all the depth of
his research over 25 years into hundreds of high tech businesses, he is
forced to conclude that success cannot be predicted from personal charac-
teristics.
He does, however, identify pointers to success among his closely defined
target group. A background of work on applied development rather than pure
research is a considerable help and the entrepreneur must be able to
transfer a considerable amount of technological knowledge from his former
employer when starting up on his own.
So, what makes an entrepreneur? And what allows some to succeed and others
to fail? The diversity of the men and women portrayed in these studies makes
for no easy conclusions. Nature and nurture both play a part, but then so
does a bewildering array of other external factors. The origins of the
entrepreneurial spark remain elusive.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page XI
</PAGE>
