<HEADLINE>
FT  24 MAR 92 / The FT Review of Business Books (23): Not just executive
toys
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL TAYLOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LEADERSHIP AND THE COMPUTER by Mary E Boone Prima Publishing Dollars 24.95,
397 pages
AUTHOR Mary E Boone was about to speak at an executive breakfast meeting in
Albuquerque. As the clatter of knives and plates died down the person
introducing her said: 'Ms Boone will talk to us today about executive
computing, a term many of us have long considered to be an oxymoron - sort
of like airline cuisine.'
Almost all surveys of senior managers show that they feel intimidated by
personal computers. Some PCs gracing executive desktops are only there for
show. Those that are switched on are often used as little more than
glorified typewriters.
Boone, a specialist on executive use of information systems and a partner in
a Connecticut management consultancy, sets out to expose the myths and
realities about executive computing and to argue that a desktop PC can give
a chief executive a competitive edge.
Her book is built around interviews with 16 senior US executives who use
PCs, exploring what they use them for and how computers help them.
Among those profiled are Burnell Roberts of Mead Corporation, who consults a
worldwide corporate contact database before leaving town; Thomas Plaskett,
who used a word processor to try and improve morale at Pan Am, the (now
defunct) airline; and Debbi Fields, who devised an expert system to help
employees make key decisions at her 600-plus Mrs Field's Cookies shops.
'Without (my computer), I don't know how I'd function . . . I'd feel totally
disconnected,' Field says.
The book suggests that computers can help executives in six basic areas:
leveraging time, communicating, coaching, staying well informed, enhancing
personal thinking, and shaping corporate culture.
If these executives consider computers so critical, why do more not use
them? 'Myths abound as to why executives are reluctant to personally use
computers,' says the author. Common misconceptions are that executives will
not type, or that adequate support staff makes computers unnecessary. 'But
the real reason executives don't use computers,' says Boone, 'is that 99 per
cent of top executives simply do not know what computers can do for them
personally. They have no idea of the power of the computer as a leadership
tool.'
In spite of their enthusiasm, most of her interviewees seem to be using
their desktops for fairly basic tasks: electronic mail, letter and speech
writing, building internal databases and contact lists, tapping into and
monitoring corporate financial data, pondering What If? scenarios on a
spreadsheet and checking spelling.
The book is readable and the interviews which make up the first half are
mostly interesting. The second half is analytical. This is a book about
management rather than computers - physical hardware is hardly mentioned.
Above all it is a book with a mission to persuade, and the author is
refreshingly honest about that.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page X
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT921-1601</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CCXBBAAVFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920324
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  24 MAR 92 / The FT Review of Business Books (22): A guide for would-be
corporate leaders
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GARETH JONES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
FRONTIERS OF LEADERSHIP by M Syrett and C Hogg Blackwell Pounds 45/Pounds
22.50, 600 pages
MANAGERS are always keen to learn more about leadership. They believe it
offers them the promise of greater personal success and perhaps enhanced
organisational effectiveness. This belief is itself sustained by a business
press which often focuses on the contribution that particular individuals
make to successful enterprises. The shelves of business bookshops groan with
manuals telling you how to become more like Lee Iacocca, John Harvey-Jones
or other business leaders.
Whether this obsession with successful individuals is really connected with
organisational effectiveness usually remains untested. Here at least is a
book laced with a healthy scepticism about leaders and the effects they can
have which at the same time recognises the importance of leadership to
organisations large and small, not least to the individuals inside them.
It attempts to bring together a variety of approaches to a series of core
questions: What do leaders do? Whatever it is, can it be learnt or
developed? How can we recognise those with leadership potential? The
contributors come from academia, consultancy, journalism and business, which
inevitably means that the collection is varied in style ranging from fairly
academic scholarly papers to semi-autobiographical insider accounts from
such as Jan Carlzon and Michael Edwardes.
It must also be said that the quality of the contributions varies
considerably. There are stimulating, even provocative pieces from Charles
Handy, John Harvey-Jones and Rosabeth Moss Kanter. In contrast, the entire
section on leadership and creativity includes essays far too brief to
develop any sustained argument or offer much practical advice. This is
partly the responsibility of the editors who have pared some contributions
too near to the bone.
What does the book offer as insights into the often muddied water of
distinguishing leadership from management? Kotter argues that we must think
of these as two distinctive, yet complementary, kinds of activity. One,
management, is essentially about coping with complexity, the other,
leadership, is about setting a direction, or building a vision. The former
uses a battery of administrative measures, - planning and budgeting,
controlling and organising - while the latter is concerned with motivating,
empowering and gaining commitment.
Clearly, organisations need both kinds of activity and we should be cautious
not to be seduced by leadership and forget the less glamorous but equally
important activities of management.
This argument may offer comfort to those inside organisations who feel the
personal risks of becoming a leader are not for them. At the same time
potential leaders are encouraged to develop and communicate their vision for
the organisation or for their part of it.
If this particular description of what leaders do convinces, what can we do
to develop such behaviour? Part II of this book deals with a series of
issues around developing leaders and placing them effectively within
organisations.
Conger's paper argues convincingly that qualities of leadership do not
spring from a set of intricate characteristics. Rather, organisations can
create processes which develop and nurture potential leaders, or they can
act to discourage or even punish those who could lead effectively.
Organisations which stifle creativity, punish dissent and drain enthusiasm
drive leadership out of the system while those that welcome unconventional
thinking and a willingness to take risks encourage it.
If Conger is right, then internal processes of management development are
critical for future success. Gratton usefully summarises current practices
and trends in identifying high-potential individuals. However, the whole
philosophy of 'fast-tracking' particular individuals is subject to withering
criticism from Wendy Hirsh, who argues that such processes are usually
unsuccessful and act as a demonstration for those not selected for the
fast-track.
An interesting alternative to this notion of a leadership cadre is explored
in the contributions dealing with organisational learning. Charles
Hampden-Turner and Bob Garratt are both persuasive in suggesting that it is
the individuals and organisations who possess the possibility of continuous
learning that are most likely to survive and prosper in a dynamic business
environment and that visionary leaders 'stuck' in one mode of thinking are
more of a problem than an asset.
This book may thus prove useful for those intrinsically interested in
conceptions of leadership and for those professionally concerned with
managerial and leadership development. A number of doubts remain. We still
need evidence about leadership effectiveness and we need an explanation of
why we seem so obsessed by the subject. Its attraction my be a dangerous
seduction.
Finally, the reader is not helped by the construction of the book. There is
no bibliography, not even suggested further reading; some papers contain
incomplete references which makes it difficult to follow-up interesting
ideas; and there is no description of several of the contributors.
Nevertheless, the lure of understanding leadership will take this book on to
many bookshelves.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page X
</PAGE>
