<HEADLINE>
FT  24 MAR 92 / The FT Review of Business Books (19): Barking up a wrong
track
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NICHOLAS FAITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
RAILROADS TRIUMPHANT by Albro Martin Oxford Pounds 25, 442 pages
I FEAR that Professor Martin and his distinguished publishers are guilty of
switch-selling, offering us one product and providing another.
In his Preface, Professor Martin claims that he was once introduced at a
conference as the man who made deregulation academically respectable. This
claim was based on an earlier book, Enterprise Denied, Origins of the
Decline of the American Railroad. So he should have been the ideal author
for a book answering the question he poses in the Preface, one of the most
fascinating and under-explored aspects of the social, economic and political
history of the US over the past 150 years: how did it come about that the
railroads, so crucial in creating, developing and binding together such a
disparate land-mass, were despised and rejected by a politically contentious
people who made them the scapegoat of their discontents?
Unfortunately Martin makes only the most token attempts to answer any of
these questions. Instead he gives us a fascinating, deeply personal, albeit
rambling and ill-organised, panoramic view of American railroads, from July
4 1828, the day Charles Carroll, last surviving signatory of the Declaration
of Independence, turned the first spade of earth for the first railroad in
the country, up to the present day, ten years after the century-old shackles
on the railroads operations had been removed by the Staggers Act of 1981 - a
long-overdue piece of legislation barely glanced at in this infuriating
book.
In fact the railroads had asked for trouble by their arrogance and greed.
The first warnings came as early as the 1870s with the Granger movement, a
radical rural revolt in the Mid-West by farmers angry at the excessive
prices they had to pay to get their grain to market (needless to say, Martin
has nothing to say about this crucial uprising).
Inevitably railroads were the first American industry to be regulated
('shackled', Professor Martin would say, but then the concept that they
could ever have abused their power never seems to have occurred to him).
They suffered further restrictions as a result of two world wars, whose
regulatory effects lasted far longer than the conflicts which triggered
them.
But - and this is the central political mystery of the subject - the
restrictions, particularly on long-overdue amalgamations, remained in force
long after the railroads had been reduced to impotence as a competitive
force; by the end of the 1970s trains were averaging just 12mph because of
the appalling state of the infrastructure.
Then, as a political scientist once put it, 'the American people found the
right solution after they had tried all the others', and since deregulation
the railways have been able to start repairing the neglect of generations
through amalgamations (and the hiving-off of shorter lines).
The come-back has a long way to go: the railroads are still struggling
against crippling work practices imposed by unions long ago in response to
the same abuse of power which created the original regulatory framework; and
tracks suitable for ultra-heavy freight trains are unsuited to fast
passenger traffic.
But there are numerous plans for improvements or new lines for passenger
trains on numerous routes - such as the North-Eastern Corridor from Boston
to Washington via New York, Dallas-Houston etc - where trains travelling up
to 200mph can compete with aeroplane and car. But perhaps we should not
expect the Prof. to bother with such details.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page IX
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT921-1603</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CCXBBAATFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920324
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  24 MAR 92 / The FT Review of Business Books (21): Japan for beginners
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EDWARD BALLS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
JAPAN is the second largest and one of the least understood economies in the
world. To explain how its scandal-ridden financial sector can continue to
finance the fastest growing industrial sector in the developed world
requires more than a partial knowledge of its institutions. Takatoshi Ito's
book (The Japanese Economy, MIT, Pounds 35.95) provides a worthwhile first
step.
The book gives an introduction to market economics, Japanese-style, starting
with a history of the Tokugawa era of isolationism, the Meiji restoration
and post-war drive for growth.
Monetary, fiscal and industrial policies all merit chapters while the
peculiar nature of the Japanese labour market is adequately covered. The
book concludes with a discussion of US-Japan economic conflicts; the retail
distribution system and import barriers; and asset prices and the stock
market boom-bust cycle. undergraduates, confused executives and bemused US
congressmen would all learn from this book.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page IX
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT921-1604</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CCXBBAASFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920324
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  24 MAR 92 / The FT Review of Business Books (20): Prime minister of the
board
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BERNARD TAYLOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE CORPORATE BOARD: CONFRONTINGTHE PARADOXES by Ada Demb and F Friedrich
Neubauer Oxford Pounds 27.50, 224 pages
CORPORATE governance is continually in the news today with business
scandals, company failures and legal battles involving large banks,
institutional shareholders, auditors, and with directors in the dock.
The need for reform is evident. As Ada Demb and Friedrich Neubauer say in
The Corporate Board: 'We need to bring the mechanisms for corporate
governance into line with current business reality.' As is clear from the
difficulties which the regulators and auditors are having with their
investigations of BCCI and the Maxwell empire, the scale and complexity of
business activity has outrun the existing control mechanisms.
In 1989 the world's ten largest companies taken together employed 4m people.
Their combined sales were equal to the GDP of the four Scandinavian
countries, or Canada. Businesses today rival governments in their ability to
create and distribute wealth. This puts enormous power into the hands of the
'government' of these companies - the 200 or so people who make up the
boards of directors of these ten companies  - a few people with an ambiguous
mandate, and a narrowly based 'electorate.'
Ada Demb and Friedrich Neubauer consider the problem of 'governance' not in
terms of mechanisms: the size and structure of boards, the use of audit and
remuneration committees, or relations with auditors and institutional
shareholders. Rather, the authors set out to provide a chairman or chief
executive with a set of 'diagnostic tools'.
Their frameworks are useful. They argue that 'much of the expressed
dissatisfaction with boards is, in reality, a dissatisfaction with the
performance of our entire governance system', therefore we should not focus
our attention just on board structures. Directors should also be assessing
the regulatory system, relationships with owners, and social pressures.
The authors suggest that developing a strong board is like building a
bridge. There is no universal design which will fit every case. It is a
matter of balancing the opposing forces and stresses to suit a particular
situation.
In a board there are three main sources of tension: (1) management autonomy
versus board control; (2) commitment and involvement versus detachment and
objectivity; (3) good teamwork versus the judgment and initiative of
individuals
The authors have achieved a breakthrough in management research. It is, I
believe, the first time researchers have been permitted to interview the
main board directors of large international corporations about the way they
run their boards. They questioned 72 directors of 11 large corporations in
eight countries, mostly in Europe, but also in Canada and Venezuela.
The data they have produced comes from the widest possible range of
directors: from two-tier boards and unitary boards, state-owned companies as
well as private businesses; even a couple of employee directors were
included. Surprisingly, they found that regardless of the board structure or
the industry, all the directors faced the same kinds of problems.
The price the authors had to pay for access to these directors was total
confidentiality. From the readers' point of view this is a serious drawback.
There are no company names - no case studies (not even in disguise), no
information about the organisation's size, structure, product/market
situation or performance - except that in general their performance was
'above average'. Nevertheless, the book has an air of reality because the
argument is illustrated throughout by quotations from the directors who were
interviewed.
The 'bottom line' of the book is the need for board assessments. To quote
Sir John Harvey-Jones: 'unless a board continuously criticises the way it is
working it is extraordinarily difficult for it to improve its performance'.
Even in the large corporations which the authors visited this practice was
not established, except in a few cases on an informal basis.
In the current debate about corporate governance, board assessments is
becoming a hot topic. The Working Group on Corporate Governance, a group of
distinguished lawyers representing large US companies and institutional
investors, recently recommended regular and comprehensive appraisals of
boards and individual directors by outside directors, and by institutional
shareholders.
Also, in 1990 the British Institute of Directors published a report ('The
Effective Board' by Colin Coulson-Thomas and Alan Wakelam) which recommended
that the chairman should require the board to undertake an 'annual review'
of its collective performance and the personal effectiveness of each
director. If this idea takes off, it will provide an important role for
non-executive directors, and management consultants.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page IX
</PAGE>
</DOC>
