<DOCNO>FT921-1605</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CCXBBAARFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920324
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  24 MAR 92 / The FT Review of Business Books (17): A clarion call in the
wilderness
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MAVERICK, THE LIFE OF A UNION REBEL by Eric Hammond and Christopher Leake
Weidenfield and Nicholson, Pounds 16.99, 214 pages
AT A TIME when most trade union leaders struggled to be heard amid a hostile
political environment, Eric Hammond encountered few such difficulties. When
he stepped down this month as general secretary of the EETPU electricians
after eight years, trade unions lost one of their most notorious, and
arguably one of their most effective, leaders.
Notorious because he challenged traditional views of what unions should do
and incurred the wrath of colleagues in other unions as a result. Effective
because his union suffered less than others in membership losses and he
retained the loyalty of his members even though he led them out of the
Trades Union Congress and the union mainstream.
In his autobiography, he is typically unrepentant. Indeed, he inflames his
opponents further by revealing details of secret talks held with News
International a year before it moved its newspaper printing operations to
Wapping in 1985. The talks, albeit on recognition at a planned publication
rather than existing ones, contributed towards several thousand print union
workers losing their jobs.
Hammond, never one to undersell himself, clearly has his eyes on a wider
readership than that which could normally be expected of a union leader's
autobiography. Written in collaboration with Christopher Leake, industrial
editor of The Mail on Sunday, the style is succinct and rich in anecdotes.
Among these Hammond records a confrontation at 10 Downing Street with Lord
Weinstock, GEC chief executive. The row, over whether Hammond was
responsible for frustrating a 1970s nuclear programme, ended with Hammond
asking Weinstock if he ever asked himself whether he might be wrong.
According to Hammond: 'Weinstock paused briefly and then said, with all the
vehemence I have experienced from my many enemies in the TUC: 'Yes, I was
wrong. I didn't have you shot.' There was no smile.'
The book is also readable because Hammond has a story to tell. In ten
chapters, the book uses five to chart the EETPU's and Hammond's differences
with other unions over: the pits strike of 1984-5; union acceptance of
government cash for ballots; News International; no-strike deals; and Labour
party policy.
In these rows Hammond sustained himself with his belief, bordering on
arrogance, in his intellectual rectitude. If he had doubts about his talks
with Murdoch, he does not express them. The blame is placed firmly on the
shoulders of print union leaders for their '19th century' intransigence in
talks with Murdoch and for leading their members 'like lemmings over the
precipice.'
But in his adversities Hammond's state of mind - though not necessarily his
cause - was also helped by his delight in verbal fighting and his sense of
theatre. On the few occasions where he expresses regret it is usually to
lament that he was deprived of the dramatic effect he had expected.
In one passage he discusses his last speech to the TUC, in the debate prior
EETPU's 1988 expulsion for failing to implement TUC rulings on inter-union
rows. 'For the first time in years, I was able to make a speech without
constant interruption. Norman (Willis, TUC general secretary) had issued
orders the previous evening that there was to be no heckling. I tried
desperately to bait them, but much to my chagrin it did not work.'
The overall impression Hammond tries to give is that he faced up to reality
faster than other union leaders over issues such as government cash for
ballots and single union deals. Of his struggles in the Labour party, he
writes: 'From being the odd man out all those years ago, (a reference to a
row over ceremonial dress while a Labour councillor) I now feel like the odd
man in. After all, they have all followed by lead.'
Unions and Labour have indeed altered their policies. But what changed them
was Thatcher and the Conservative party; Hammond's role was insignificant by
comparison and he may even have slowed the process because of his
antagonistic stances. And it is difficult to imagine any other union leader
emulating Hammond's actions during the News International controversies.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page VIII
</PAGE>
