<HEADLINE>
FT  24 MAR 92 / The FT Review of Business Books (15): Fair exchange shaped
by market forces
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD VIVIAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
WOLFF'S GUIDE TO THE LONDON METAL EXCHANGE (4th. edition) Metal Bulletin
Books Pounds 44 (Dollars 88), 269 pages
THE TIN MEN by Ralph Kestenbaum Metal Bulletin Books Pounds 25, 316 pages
THE latest edition of Wolff's Guide, edited by former FT Commodities Editor
John Edwards, is renewed testimony to the long-standing, hand-in-glove
relationship between the London Metal Exchange (LME) and Rudolf Wolff &amp; Co.,
one of its founder members in 1876 and now one of the elder statesmen of the
metal-broking fraternity.
Different chapters by various contributors cover in detail the LME's history
from its early days in City coffee houses, how metal trading is conducted,
the theory and practice of hedging, traded options, chart analysis, and the
six metals traded on the exchange. Appendices list LME members, brands of
deliverable metal, locations of LME warehouses and contract specifications.
An index might have been useful, although the publishers might justifiably
argue that the contents are so well arranged that the reader can find his
way around without an index.
A more obvious omission, particularly from the many worked examples of
trading strategies, is any meaningful reference to dealing costs. How can
one be sure that a complicated hedging programme will not cost more in
commission than it is worth in trading gains?
Of the 22 chapters in this edition, eight are new and several others have
had to be revised since the previous edition in 1988.
Trading on the LME has changed in several respects since then, with the
advent of traded options, settlement in a choice of currencies, worldwide
points of delivery and a trading 'horizon' extended from three to 27 months
forward.
Furthermore, the LME has had to restructure itself in the wake of both the
1985 tin market crisis and the 1986 Financial Services Act, both for its own
protection and to redefine the relationship between its brokers and their
clients.
The concept of investor protection now extends to speculators and even trade
hedgers on commodity markets, and the LME's clearing house, which guarantees
the execution of every contract, ensures that brokers are protected as much
from each other as from their clients.
A consistent theme running through the book is the LMF, as the embodiment of
irresistible free market forces, prevailing over the evils of price
manipulation by both metal producers and speculators.
This market is the dog which, unlike others, no cartelised or speculative
tail can wag. It is the perfect hedging medium because it discovers the
definitive free market price - because it is the perfect hedging medium.
Ralph Kestenbaum's The Tin Men is a long overdue account of the most famous
recent attempt to use the LME to rig a market. Kestenbaum, who led the LME
brokers in their claims for redress from the International Tin Council
(ITC), is particularly well placed to write this authoritative if not
unbiased account.
By October 1985 the ITC and its 22 member governments had run up a bill of
Pounds 900m on the LME's tin market, which it then decided not to pay.
Kestenbaum takes us through the web of contradictions, conflicts of
interest, doublespeak and humbug which allowed the ITC to get into this
position.
He also corrects a popular misconception: that the scandal of the tin crisis
was simply about the collapse in prices. More to the point was, first, that
tin prices should never have been as high as they were to begin with; and
second, that the price collapse was accompanied by the ITC's refusal to pay
its bills.
The politicians and bureaucrats who claimed to run the ITC deserve to be
highly embarrassed by this reminder of their folly.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page VII
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT921-1609</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CCXBBAANFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920324
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  24 MAR 92 / The FT Review of Business Books (12): How the West slew the
Asian dragon
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW FREEMAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE POLITICAL ECONOMY OF MERCHANT EMPIRES, 1350-1750 edited by James Tracy
Cambridge Pounds 35, 504 pages
TRADE disputes between the Western economies and Japan are a feature of
modern life, so it is useful to remember that anything resembling free trade
between these states is a relatively recent development. Go a little way
back in history and there was almost no trade at all.
The central question this volume of stimulating essays sets out to explore
is why, in the space of a few centuries, the European states were able to
achieve a dominant position in global trade at the expense of often
well-organised and financed rivals, mainly in Asia.
The book examines several possible explanations. It might be argued, for
example, that the Europeans simply had better means of transport, or better
business methods including more sophisticated forms of credit. Even if Asian
business methods were in no way inferior, the Europeans were able to
overwhelm them by making devastating use of their superior armaments to
further their commercial aims.
Alternatively, the Europeans succeeded because in the likes of the East
India Companies and Portugal's Estado da India, they created forms of
organisation in which the use of violence was subordinated to the rational
pursuit of profit.
As James Tracy points out in his introduction: 'The principal feature that
differentiates European enterprises from indigenous trade networks in
various part of the globe . . . was that they organised their major
commercial ventures either as an extension of the state or as autonomous
trading companies with many of the characteristics of the state.' That
included the capacity to wage war.
Given that European traders saw themselves as beset by enemies wherever they
looked, perhaps that was just as well. The fears of Europeans stationed in
Asia were informed partly by national rivalries, but mainly by the fact that
they were all interlopers. Most historians agree that before the Europeans
arrived, Asian trade had been relatively peaceful.
Geoffrey Parker shows in a perceptive essay how Asians were appalled at the
Europeans' destructive style of warfare. He nevertheless shows that the
notion of Western powers bent on world domination is anachronistic.
Most traders, the Dutch being the notable exception, undertook military
action only either to coerce reluctant buyers or in order to safeguard
themselves against attack from their European rivals.
The book is a companion to The Rise of Merchant Empires, which dealt with
the changes in the growth and composition of long-distance trade over the
same period.
The two volumes emerged from a conference in 1987. Between them they take
the debate over the origins of modern trade to new heights.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page VI
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT921-1610</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CCXBBAAMFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920324
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  24 MAR 92 / The FT Review of Business Books (13): Liberalisation: a
policy for insurance
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER MONTAGNON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
OBSTACLES TO THE LIBERALISATION OF TRADE IN INSURANCE by Robert Carter and
Gerard Dickinson Harvester Wheatsheaf (for the Trade Policy Research Centre)
Pounds 14.95, 208 pages
OF ALL the service industries due be liberalised as a result of the Uruguay
Round of international trade negotiations, insurance is one of the most
tricky.
This is not only because of the complex nature of the business. Foreign
participation in a country's insurance industry tends to be particularly
sensitive because it involves the collection and mobilisation of national
savings as well as protecting residents from risks.
This book offers a concise but broad-ranging description of the issues
concerned. Though only about 11 per cent of non-life insurance premiums
world-wide are written by foreign suppliers, foreign supply of reinsurance
amounts to 33 per cent.
The authors argue that there would be substantial benefits from
liberalisation. The balance of payments risks are smaller than many
developing countries fear, while consumers would gain from greater choice of
product, lower premiums and, sometimes, more expert advice on loss
prevention.
The more useful aspect is the way in which Carter and Dickinson show why the
right of establishment is so essential to any effort to liberalise the
direct insurance industry and why regulatory differences matter so much.
Foreign suppliers can suffer discrimination in a number of ways, ostensibly
because this is necessary to protect the customer. They may, for example, be
subject to greater capital requirements or barred from certain types of
business. The description that is built up of the obstacles to trade in
insurance is one that will come in handy for any layman trying to understand
insurance in the context of the overall debate on trade in services.
That said, there are drawbacks. One suspects that this book has been rather
hastily dusted down after a long period of mouldering on the shelf while the
Trade Policy Research Centre sorted out its own problems. Thus it is
somewhat surprising to see references to the Soviet approach to insurance
and to 'communist' countries like Hungary. Equally, too little is made of
the difficulties of committing federal governments to liberalise when, as is
the case with the US, it is the individual states rather than central
government that are responsible for regulation.
Nor does the book dwell on the context of US determination to break into the
potentially lucrative markets of South-east Asia which has been a potent
force behind the Gatt discussion. It does, however, provide insight into the
way the European Community has struggled to open up its internal market.
It ends with some practical advice from two authors long familiar with the
industry. First, it would be better to seek regulatory equivalence rather
than outright harmonisation of regulation; second, regulators should be
prepared to accept the principle of home country control for insurance sold
across frontiers.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page VI
</PAGE>
</DOC>
