FT  24 MAR 92 / The FT Review of Business Books (14): At last - the bumper
book of facts
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW FREEMAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE ECONOMIST YEAR BOOK 1992 Economist Books Pounds 25, 340 pages
ATTENTION all fans of the Economist. At last you can throw away those unruly
piles of back issues with a clear conscience, for the first Economist Year
Book contains everything the average reader will want to remember about 1991
and more.
It should appeal to those who tire of the magazine's flippant content -
there is a welcome air of seriousness about the work. The pages are clearly
laid out along familiar divisions and the statistical section is as useful
as anything on the market. The Year Book should eventually build into a fine
reference collection. But readers will need to buy an aspidistra or two to
fill up their shelves in the meantime.
