<HEADLINE>
FT  24 MAR 92 / The FT Review of Business Books (11): Eco shopping list
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER MARSH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
WEALTH BEYOND MEASURE: AN ATLAS OF NEW ECONOMICS by Paul Ekins, Mayer
Hillman and Robert Hutchison Gaia Books Pounds 9.99, 191 pages
RARELY has there been a better time for the environmental movement to
formulate new theories about how human development might occur in a way that
harms the planet less and spreads wealth more evenly.
Wealth Beyond Measure seeks to provide a structure of 'green economics'
according to which, its authors explain, the world would develop with the
pursuit of industrial growth no longer the main economic objective. The new
framework would encompass values including 'tight sustainability
constraints', 'positive human values' and 'personal development and quality
of life'.
Although it is difficult to argue against any of these concepts, the book
fails to link them into a convincing alternative vision of how the planet
could evolve. Much of the volume appears to have been written by a committee
bent on referring to just about every vaguely radical idea of the past 20
years.
It thus moves erratically between discussing improvements to the Common
Agricultural Policy, the problems of too many cars, and the misdemeanours of
Ernest Saunders. There is much that is pious and ill thought-out, as in the
pseudoscientific discussion of the connections between environmental damage
and technology and in the contentious arguments about the moral fibre of
people being harmed by too much shopping.
Anyone who wants to think about economics in a different way would find a
good check list here of topics, but a less than coherent book.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page V
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT921-1613</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CCXBBAAJFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920324
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  24 MAR 92 / The FT Review of Business Books (9): The threat of green
protectionism
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER MONTAGNON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE GREENING OF WORLD TRADE ISSUES edited by Kym Anderson and Richard
Blackhurst Harvester Wheatsheaf Pounds 40/Pounds 13.99, 275 pages
EVEN BEFORE the Uruguay Round of multilateral trade negotiations draws to a
close, new issues are piling up on the agenda of the General Agreement on
Tariffs and trade.
Sir Leon Brittan, the UK's senior European Commissioner, recently confirmed
what many trade experts have accepted for some time - that competition
policy will feature large in trade negotiations of the future. This book
deals with the other, and possibly more urgent issue of the 1990s: the link
between trade and environment policy.
It is not difficult to see why the two are related. The bottom line for
trade policy is, after all, the location of jobs. The ultimate reason why
Italy has fought to keep Japanese cars out of its home market is to preserve
employment at Fiat. Environmental controls may, however, distort the
international competitive conditions in which particular industries operate.
As a result, jobs may be lost and growth opportunities jeopardised.
There are already several examples of how environmental policy can clash
with the free trade principles espoused by the Gatt. The US embargo on
Mexican tuna which was imposed to protect the dolphin is one such case.
European aluminium makers are complaining about the way in which Russian
producers, who do not face strict pollution controls, are flooding the West
with cheap products. Conservationist lobby groups in the rich developed
world have succeeded in curbing trade in African ivory.
The Greening of World Trade Issues explores the link between trade policy
and the environment from a number of perspectives. How far are 'solutions'
to environmental problems likely to provoke trade friction? How far is there
a conflict, as some US environmentalists claim, between the ideals of free
trade and environmental protection? Will it be necessary to use trade
incentives to persuade countries such as Brazil to protect the rain forest?
And, if so, will this also conflict with the ideal of non-discriminatory
free trade.
While recognising the legitimacy of environmentalist aims, the book argues
that the impact of certain policies on the trading environment could be
enormous. Severe restrictions on the use of coal, for example, would be a
threat to the China's development prospects.
Since some compromises will have to be made, it is all the more imperative
that the right policy approach is chosen. Some environmentalists argue that
trade liberalisation is a priori harmful because it increases consumption,
but this need not be the case. Liberalisation of world farm trade could help
by reducing the use of pesticides in over-farmed industrial countries.
The book takes the form of a carefully structured series of essays
originally written as background papers for the recent Gatt report on
International Trade 1990-1. It should be noted that this is a book written
by economists for economists. A large part of it is taken up with the
development of models showing the impact of various environmental policies
on the trading system and vice versa.
The underlying message is, however, clear. There is a real fear of an unholy
alliance between environmentalist and protectionist lobbies which could be
seriously counter-productive. Indeed, as the book concludes: 'It is even
possible that protectionist groups would manipulate the design or
implementation of environmental measures to such a degree that the net
effect would be an increase in environmental degradation.'
Trade policy-makers must therefore alert themselves to the implications of
the environment debate. In particular, a clear idea is needed as to what set
of policies would best meet both the objectives of free trade and
environmental protection. There is a clear preference in the book for a
market orientated approach, even possibly involving the freedom to auction
'pollution permits.'
There is a difficulty with this kind of approach in that a windfall benefit
would accrue to firms which sold their permits. Similarly, the idea of a
worldwide tax on polluters raises questions about how the proceeds should be
distributed. However, many other controls favoured by environmentalists,
such as production restraints or process and product standards, lend
themselves more readily to abuse by protectionists.
While the argument over policy rages, the risk is that all sorts of
protectionist measures will be introduced in the name of the environment.
The academics will have to refine their argument quickly and ensure they get
a proper public airing, if the baby is not to be lost with the bathwater.
This book, and the recent Gatt report, constitute an admirable effort,
though they are only a start.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
