<HEADLINE>
FT  24 MAR 92 / The FT Review of Business Books (10): Trade and the poverty
trap
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID DODWELL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE TRADE TRAP: POVERTY AND THE GLOBAL COMMODITY MARKETS by Belinda Coote
Oxfam Pounds 5.95, 214 pages
MANY POOR developing countries appear to be caught in a trap: during a
decade in which some have become even poorer, the commodities which they
export have fallen steadily in price. The trend appears irreversible. Trade
barriers have made the transition to higher-value-added processing a fraught
one.
The problems are real. It is good that Oxfam, in its latest publication,
should focus attention on them. However, it is astonishing that it should
have come to the conclusion that managed trade through charitably-based
'alternative trading organisations' in the west, and 'development friendly
consumerism' provides any serious solution to such problems.
The most disappointing aspect of the book is that it may be the only one on
trade and developing countries that many interested readers see in the UK
this year: it is saddening that such a glib and simplistic assessment of
Third World problems, hyped by Oxfam's powerful publicity machine, is likely
to have such influence.
The book's case studies, based on Oxfam's extensive field experience in the
developing world, provide interesting and valuable material. But the
sentimental analysis has roots in the sort of dogma that used to exude from
the (now metamorphosing) Unctad during the 1970s: blame for the poor's
problems must be laid at the door of multinationals which rape a country's
resources unfettered by national control, exploiting the poor, and ruining
their environment; a rich men's club controls the rules of world trade, and
exploits them ruthlessly at the expense of the poor.
Where is necessary attention paid to the importance of local wars and the
diversion of precious funds to military spending, to local corruption,
massively inefficient state planning systems, uncontrolled population
growth? Where is an effort to explain why some countries in the developing
world have escaped poverty while others have remained mired?
It is almost cruel to suggest to farmers in the Third World that salvation
might be found in 'alternative trading organisations' that provide the same
distorted price and market signals that protectionism and state socialism
have provided so damagingly in the past.
It is just such muddled logic that has led to the cossetting of Europe's
farmers through the Common Agriculture Policy (CAP) that costs European
taxpayers so dear, and so damages world prices for the commodities on which
exporters from the Third World depend.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page V
</PAGE>
