<HEADLINE>
FT  24 MAR 92 / The FT Review of Business Books (7): How the City's boats
were burnt
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID KYNASTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE CITY OF LONDON: CONTINUITY AND CHANGE by Ranald C Mitchie Macmillan
Pounds 30, 238 pages
THE SCENE: a London dinner-party in the 1850s.
Thackeray's daughter: 'And what is your profession?'
The man from Barings: 'A merchant.'
Miss Thackeray: 'A merchant] I picture you to myself sitting at your desk by
an open window overlooking the broad estuary of the Thames. You glance from
time to time at the distant reaches of the river. Presently you see a noble
ship taking advantage of the incoming tide. She is yours and she is laden
with precious tribute from foreign countries . . .'
THERE ARE not many noble ships coming up the Thames in Ranald C. Michie's
City, nor for that matter merchants gossiping on 'Change, nor stockbrokers
being hammered, nor black-coated clerks scrawling away laboriously at
sloping desks. Altogether this is a book short on City atmosphere.
Does it matter? The answer is broadly 'no', for what Michie has provided
instead is a well-organised, challenging and in many ways pioneering
technical history of the modern City.
In four central chapters - 'Commercial City', 'Credit City', 'Capital City',
'Client City' - he divides the City into what he sees as having been its key
functional components, and within them he gives a tightly argued
chronological overview of each.
There is relatively little archival research, but he has done what no one
has had either the insight or the stamina to do before, which is to read and
draw appropriate conclusions from a thousand unambitious histories of a
thousand unambitious, niche firms - that cumulative corporate history of the
myriad-like, disintegrated City before it all changed.
The most striking of these chapters is the one on the Commercial City.
Michie shows that up to 1914, and arguably up to 1939, the City was
predominantly a commercial centre rather than a financial one. This was less
through its handling of physical trade, important though that was until the
port of London's post-1945 decline, but was connected to all the major
commercial centres by telegraph and 'the result of this communications
revolution was that it became possible to conduct a global trading business
from an office in the City.'
And, often through the ill-appreciated work of continental immigrants, the
City before 1914 'was the only commercial centre in the world that possessed
the range and depth of personnel, experience, institutions and facilities to
handle the increasingly large and complex network of international trade.'
Now it is very different. The two world wars cost the City dear in lost
contacts and expertise; the end of Empire, informal as well as formal, broke
many ties with London; the commodity markets after 1945 only falteringly
returned to free trading; and the City merchant became almost an
anachronism. There have been growth areas - such as in countertrade - but
overall the picture is one of decline.
What has at least partially come to the square mile's rescue is Client City
 -by which Michie means a whole range of client-orientated services,
including accountancy and merchant banking, all activities which have risen
in importance while market-based activities have dwindled. Michie is perhaps
over-schematic about this - is securities trading, for instance, a
client-based or market-based activity? - but it is a new way of looking at
the City's more recent history that demands consideration.
A final chapter takes the long-swing approach. He sees 1914 to 1971 (when
fixed exchange rates broke down) as a regrettable, over-regulated hiatus,
and interprets the era since then as a chequered attempt to return to the
'normal' pre-1914 world of unfettered capital flows.
He is neither bull nor bear about the City's future, though one senses a
scepticism as to whether the City will really 'ensure that competitive
forces pervade all its markets and services.' And he considers briskly the
old chestnut of the City's responsibility for British economic decline,
concluding that since both City and the larger economy have been in relative
decline since 1945, they are probably both part of the same problem.
All in all, not a book for a budding novelist, but the man from Barings
should take it on board.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page IV
</PAGE>
</DOC>
