<HEADLINE>
FT  24 MAR 92 / The FT Review of Business Books (6): The greed behind the
glamour
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BARRY RILEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
FRAUD: PREVENTION AND DETECTION by Ian Huntington Butterworths Pounds 55,
234 pages
A COMPANY once claimed that a large part of its profits were earned on
exports by an overseas subsidiary. But an investigator found that the
subsidiary's claimed sales figures far exceeded the exports recorded in the
particular country's own Official statistics.
Fraud is a topical subject and this comprehensive book is being published at
a time when many businesses and their auditors and other consultants are
concerned at the risks.
How can fraud be deterred or, if all else fails, at any rate detected? Ian
Huntington, a partner with KPMG Peat Marwick, and currently at the Serious
Fraud Office, packs a great deal of expert knowledge into this book,
although he confesses that there is a risk that not only investigators but
also potential new fraudsters might learn something about the tricks of the
trade.
Sensitive antennae are required. The author mentions the case, for example,
of a Far East bank branch where an investigator noticed that the accounting
machines were being used on a Sunday. It turned out that key customers of
the branch were routinely allowed to produce their own versions of their
bank statements.
This book is not, however, intended to be a popular exposition of various
entertaining scams, but rather a step-by-step guide to how the risks can be
minimised. Fraud is 'concealed stealing' says the author. The task is
therefore to make it more difficult for rogues to hide payments or invent
transactions.
Various standard dodges can be checked for, and fraudsters entrenched in an
organisation may at least be discouraged if they fear that new systems
increase the risks of discovery. Nevertheless it will always be harder to
catch the more slippery characters who are capable of innovation.
Ian Huntington provides instructions on how to carry out a fraud
'health-check' and gives checklists for investigators. Fraud, he admits, may
be clever, and it may even seem glamorous. But he points out that the
fraudsters are motivated by nothing more attractive than pure greed. Those
seeking to deal with fraud must begin by casting aside any mystique and
focusing on the unpleasant underlying reality.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page III
</PAGE>
