<DOCNO>FT921-1618</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CCXBBAAEFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920324
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  24 MAR 92 / The FT Review of Business Books (4): The changing world of
competition
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SANJAYA LALL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
RIVAL STATES, RIVAL FIRMS: COMPETTION FOR WORLD MARKET SHARES by John
Stopford and Susan Strange Cambridge, 321 pages
THIS BOOK is the result of an unusual collaboration by two eminent
specialists. Stopford is a leading business school researcher, while Strange
is well known for her publications on international relations. They have
taken on the subject of the relations between multinationals and governments
in developing countries, covering under this heading the gamut of topics
from technical change and development strategy to the nitty gritty of
decision making in business and bargaining with officials.
The setting is apt. World flows of foreign direct investment (FDI)are
booming. After a slackening of activity in the early 1980s, a sustained
burst of energy and optimism has seized the multinationals. Their
international activity is now spreading faster than world trade or
production. The increasing share of global industry and services accounted
for by MNCs is regarded with welcome rather than resentment or fear by most
governments in the developing countries. The growing pace of technical
change, along with revolutionary improvements in transport, communications
and financial markets, binds all countries closer together in a web of
competition and cooperation, with MNCs among the leading players,
While these are not new trends, the current boom in FDI differs in several
ways from that in the 60s and 70s. The US, once the largest net exporter of
capital, is now the largest recipient. There are several major new players
in the world league, from Japan, Europe and even the developing countries.
However, the share of FDl going to developing countries, once rising, is now
declining, and the real value of flows to them in 1989-90 was lower than a
dozen years previously The flows have also changed direction and become more
concentrated. Just when governments are clamouring for more FDI, the
investors, driven by the needs of global competition and the search for
efficient locations (with skilled labour, good infrastructure,reliable local
suppliers and conducive legal environments), are focusing on the relatively
advanced countries in East and South-east Asia. Success in attracting FDl
is, in other words, directly linked with success in industrial strategy more
generally, one reinforcing the other.
What then accounts for the success of East Asia, in particular for the
historically unprecedented growth and Industrial prowess of Korea and
Taiwan? A common perception is that they developed' by pursuing liberal
market-oriented policies and relying heavily on MNCs.
This simple view is unrealistic and misleading. Markets are never as
efficient as theories make out, and in developing countries they are very
prone to 'failure'. The success of Korea and Taiwan is due to the pervasive
and prolonged interventions they undertook to remedy such failures, by
building up education, protecting infant industries, fostering indigenous
technological activity, setting up numerous institutions, and promoting
local enterprise by restricting foreign entry. They were certainly export
oriented,and the pattern oftheir interventions differed radically from that
in most other developing countries- but they intervened nonetheless. If they
are the role models, governments retain the central role in development.
They can still be the guardians of national interest rather than a
collection of bumbling, corrupt bureaucrats.
This is the view taken by the authors of this book. They debunk many of the
simplistic notions that seem to pervade much of development thinking. They
survey evidence from a range of firms and from three countries (Brazil,
Kenya and Malaysia) to illustrate how complex,even bewildering, is the real
world of decision making in politics and business, and how difficult it is
to define ideal strategies.
They stress the fundamentals of economic progress (the chapter by Henley is
very good) and emphasise how technological change calls for human resource
development and astute, flexible policy responses by governments. They do
not directly address the issue of optimal interventions, but that may be
because they do not see a generalisable pattern of policies for diverse
countries.
In their view, governments and MNCs have much to gain from each other.
However, their relations are not always complementary. It is inherent in the
nature of the phenomenon that conflicts of interest can arise between MNCs
and developing countries, and it is only governments that can resolve them.
In the past the resolution has often been biased and harmful, and better
understanding of technological realities and business can help to improve
policy making in the future. The book closes with many sensible suggestions
for both parties.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page III
</PAGE>
