<HEADLINE>
FT  24 MAR 92 / The FT Review of Business Books (5): Big bucks and dirty
laundry
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DOMINICK COYLE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE MONEY LAUNDERERS by Robert E Powis Probus Europe Pounds 15.95, 328 pages
THERE has got to be a great movie in this book. It has everything to
fascinate and to titillate - from mobsters to sex, crooked bank employees
and indifferent bank managers, drug peddlers and money launderers,
smoke-filled rooms and bent politicians, fast cars, yachts and aircraft. At
the core: how the drug barons and their hordes of henchmen and small-time
crooks launder the estimated Dollars 120bn (Pounds 68.1bn) which Americans
spend on drugs every year.
This tale is very much what Americans call a big buck ticket; the numbers
are big, and so are the names, from the collapsed Bank of Credit and
Commerce International (BCCI) to former Panamanian dictator General Manuel
Noriega. Big name banks, who either colluded in the re-cycling of drug money
or were duped by the crooks include, according to this account, Bank of
America, Manufacturers Hanover, Crocker National, Citibank, Chemical, Bank
of New England- indeed, the great and the good of the banking world who did
not know, or did not want to know, the difference between real money and
sleaze money.
First a definition: money laundering amounts to the use of money derived
from illegal activities by concealing the identity of the individuals who
obtained the cash, and converts it to assets that appear to have come from a
legitimate source. This author's definition is more straight-forward: the
washing of dirty money to make it appear clean.
And he should know. Robert Powis is a former US Secret Service agent who
served in Washington as a top Treasury official coordinating enforcement
against money laundering and was also involved in the administration of the
Bank Secrecy Act. Powis writes it as he says it was over the past 20 years,
and still is to a large extent, despite more and more legislation and more
enforcement. He calculates that some 80 per cent of money from illegal US
drug sales finds its way into the American banking system, often with the
knowledge of greedy bankers anxious for ever more deposits; the rest takes
wing, mainly via banks in Switzerland and Italy, and some in seemingly
legitimate gold and jewellery businesses in London.
A little - everything is relative when the annual sum touches on Dollars
120bn - even finds it way in covert operations run by the Central
Intelligence Agency, such as the Contra affair which former President Ronald
Reagan said he knew nothing about. Powis throws no new light on this.
Facts are there aplenty. Witness a small motel room in the American
Mid-West: a group of 'smurfs', so called by Treasury special agents after
the blue cherubs made famous in television cartoons, whose task it was to
launder drug money by using the local Yellow Pages to check out bank
addresses and be assigned to branches where they would open accounts, or
obtain bearer cheques, for something short of Dollars 10,000. This is the
maximum over which banks must (or should) conform with the 1970 Bank Secrecy
Act requiring that they report to the Internal Revenue Service currency
transactions over Dollars 10,000 on behalf of the same person on the same
day. The 'smurfs' stopped a dollar short, and most banks willingly bought
the re-cycled drugs money.
'A smurf could dispose of between Dollars 50,000 and Dollars 100,000 in cash
each day, and typically be paid between 0.5 and 1.5 per cent, depending upon
his experience and ability. A smurf who disposed of Dollars 100,000 would be
paid somewhere between Dollars 500 and Dollars 1,000 for a day's work. The
individual in charge of a road trip would get about 1.5 per cent of all the
money laundered; in addition, he would get 0.5 per cent of all currency that
he personally laundered at banks.'
The whole business become labour-intensive, and new and bigger ways were
arranged, often involving flying the money out of the US to Mexico or
Switzerland; indeed, at one point some dishonest airline stewards with deep
pockets were recruited to do the work, at a price. Some existing Italian
resort apartment complexes are monuments to this re-cycling process, says
Powis.
But his is not just a cracking yarn. He has much that is useful to say about
the need for stricter compliance procedures in banks around the world,
particularly his reference to the 'Know your client' philosophy.
He admires the so-called Basle Agreement, under which the Group of 10
industrial nations have agreed principles to try and limit the re-cycling of
illicit cash through the banking system, but suggests that much more needs
to be done within the US banking system itself. He thinks that politicians
are hard on the regulators and soft on the drugs barons, not out of
misplaced sympathy but because of concern about how the policemen police the
crooks, including their occasional short cuts which erode individual rights.
All in all, quite a read - and watch out for the movie.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page III
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT921-1620</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CCXBBAACFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920324
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  24 MAR 92 / The FT Review of Business Books (3): Facts to be appreciated
before depreciation
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EDWARD BALLS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
WHAT'S NEW IN ECONOMICS? edited by Jim Maloney Manchester University Press
Pounds 40,326 pages
FEW assets depreciate as fast as a book on new developments in economics.
Even the economic journals are generally a year or two out of date by the
time they are published. Keeping up to date with the latest research instead
involves wading through vast mail-bags of working papers.
Only a small band of the committed have either the time or the inclination
to read all the new papers in any field. Much new research is, in any case,
a new variation on a broader theme which evolves at a more gradual pace.
The nine contributors to What's New In Economics? have done the donkey work
on everyone else's behalf. Each essay covers a broad theme in economics -
labour, industrial, international monetary economics, etc - and examines how
research in that field has evolved over the past decade or so.
Written for an economically-literate but non-mathematical audience, most of
the essays are mercifully short on equations while not skimping on either
graphs or references. Most of the fashionable subjects are covered: the
application of game theory to industry, the 'micro-foundations' of
macroeconomics, imperfect competition and international trade theory.
Not all the chapters are complete: the discussion of labour economics, for
example, appears to omit efficiency wages, perhaps the most important strand
of labour research in recent years; while the macroeconomics chapter omits
any reference to the blossoming new endogenous growth literature. All of the
contributions would have benefited from a greater attention to empirical
research.
Overall, though, this book is well worth the effort. Read it soon; it will
be out of date by Christmas.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page II
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT921-1621</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CCXBBAABFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920324
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  24 MAR 92 / The FT Review of Business Books (2): The coalition that
calmed a crisis
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By WILLIAM ST CLAIR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
NATIONAL CRISIS AND NATIONAL GOVERNMENT 1926-1932 by Philip Williamson
Cambridge Pounds 60, 569 pages
THE DECISION to return sterling to the gold standard was one of the many
disastrous mistakes of the inter-war years.
The intention to return was announced in November 1918, in the exuberant
month when the war ended. It was regarded as a long-term policy aspiration
of no immediate relevance and nobody took much notice. But political
promises which benefit particular groups are not forgotten. From the
beginning, the debate was not about whether to return to fixed exchange
rates, but when.
The promise was eventually redeemed in 1925 by Churchill when he was
chancellor. The date was chosen for no better reason than that the
government wanted to avoid having to ask Parliament for a renewal of the Act
by which gold payments had been suspended.
Despite the huge and differing disruptions and inflations that had occurred
in the world's economies since 1914, the pound was pegged at the pre-war
rate of Dollars 4.86. Seldom has a decision of such national importance been
taken with so little thought.
To many eyes, the exchange rate was a technical matter to be left to
bankers. Others saw it in terms of national prestige. The Bank of England,
still entirely independent of government, was well aware that, at that time,
most British investments abroad were in fixed interest bonds. If exporting
industry was rendered hopelessly uncompetitive at par, then, it argued,
manufacturers should cut their costs.
The UK, already in deep depression, was to pay a heavy price for this folly
as the downward spiral was reinforced with falling demand leading to yet
more unemployment, business failures, and social misery. The losses from the
decision were estimated by Keynes at over 10 per cent of national output
every year.
The interesting book by Philip Williamson, National Crisis and National
Government, tells how the mistake was eventually reversed. He describes day
by day the course of events which led to the financial crisis of July 1931
and the replacement of the minority Labour government by the coalition of
Conservatives, 'National Liberals' and a rump of Labour ministers who
followed Macdonald into the National Government.
Williamson has assiduously explored the papers of most of the actors in the
drama. He shows how they responded to the pressures, new and unexpected, and
follows the shifting alliances and compromises, both party and personal, as
the crisis unfolded.
His book is political history in a narrow sense, largely confined to the
tumble of events as seen and interpreted by politicians at Westminster. No
attempt is made to analyse the different options that were open to the
government or to trace the real effects of the decisions taken. But as a
study of how politics actually works his book has a relentless fascination.
When the exchange rate came under pressure, it became accepted that what the
country needed was 'retrenchment', meaning principally a cut in unemployment
relief.
The unemployed, it was argued, had benefited from the fall in prices. But
then so had the owners of the gilts by which the war had been financed. In
an attempt to buy the good-will of foreign financiers, the National
Government imposed a further huge dose of deflation on a suffering nation.
Taxes were raised by 10 per cent. Public service pay was cut, that of
teachers by 15 per cent. Even when mutinies broke out in the Navy, when
India looked set to be dragged down in the wake, and overt class war in the
streets seemed inevitable, the policy was persisted with in a display of
stolid tenacity reminiscent of the generals of the Somme. Only Keynes, Bevin
and Mosley (who was not yet a fascist) showed any understanding of the real
issues and choices, along with the old-fashioned patriot, the Marquess of
Lothian.
In the end, the Bank itself stopped gold payments on its own authority, to
the amazement of Labour politicians. 'They never told us we could do that,'
they were to complain later, and not without justice.
For, contrary to expectation, the heavens did not fall. Indeed, things
immediately started to get better. The fall in sterling was modest, and
within months there was a clear revival of economic activity and a reduction
in unemployment which was to continue unabated over subsequent years.
The National Government had its reward. In the general election of October
1931, the coalition whose only reason for coming together had been to resist
devaluation at all costs, and which had been overwhelmed in the attempt, was
re-elected with the biggest majority in history. They were secure to make
further disastrous decisions involving repression in India and appeasement
of the dictators in Europe.
The story that Williamson's book tells is deeply depressing. At a time when
many voices favour the fixed exchange rates of the ERM, and when there is
talk of giving responsibility for monetary policy to an independent central
bank, it is of more than historical interest.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page II
</PAGE>
