<DOCNO>FT921-1622</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CCXBBAAAFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920324
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  24 MAR 92 / The FT Review of Business Books (1): Not one of us . . . /
Review of the sorry tale of Peter Clowes, and finds that the City must share
the blame
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD LAMBERT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE BARLOW CLOWES AFFAIR by Lawrence Lever Macmillan Pounds 17.50, 277 pages
THE Barlow Clowes affair, they will tell you in the Square Mile, was not a
City scandal. The chap was a complete outsider: no one had even heard of him
until he went bust.
It is true that Peter Clowes - the head of the failed investment company,
who was recently sentenced to 10 years in prison for stealing millions of
pounds of investors' money - was never remotely part of Britain's financial
establishment. But the first conclusion to be drawn from Lawrence Lever's
impressive book is that Barlow Clowes was a City scandal in this important
respect: he could never have got as far as he did, or duped as many gullible
investors, if he had not been able to exploit the infrastructure of the
great financial and commercial institutions in the City of London.
There is no suggestion that any of them realised that Clowes was a crook, or
willingly went along with his wrongdoing. But the truly remarkable feature
is that they were prepared to do business with a man whose activities - to
judge by this account - would have been laughable if they had not been so
ruinous.
Peter Clowes gained credibility by the fact that he had highly respectable
advisers: Herbert Smith as lawyers, Spicer and Pegler as auditors. 'The
business has now engaged reputable City firms of solicitors and accountants
to advise them on their activities . . . I recommend that the licences
should be granted without further delay,' wrote a Department of Trade and
Industry adviser in a submission that was to legitimise Clowes' UK
activities.
Top merchant banks - Lazard, Warburg, and Rothschild - unwittingly helped
him to syphon money out of his clients' accounts by extending back-to-back
loans. Under these arrangements, Clowes was able to borrow large sums from
the banks for his own use on security which actually belonged to clients.
Two clearing banks, Midland and Lloyds, continued to process his
instructions to transfer funds out of the offshore investors' accounts even
after suggestions that something funny was afoot. In Lever's words: 'Without
their innate caution, Clowes could never have gone as far as he did.'
The picture that emerges is of a man who by a combination of luck and brazen
effrontery was able to steal many millions of pounds from under the very
noses of the regulatory authorities. The story is rife with examples of
messages that were ignored by the relevant authorities or did not get
through to the right person. Information was held by different regulators in
discrete pockets, instead of being brought together to reveal the whole
picture.
No one wanted to be responsible for the drama which would follow from
closing Barlow Clowes: no one had enough initiative to step outside the
immediate sphere of regulatory influence and ask the big questions. Everyone
wanted to pass the buck.
Thus, when the crucial licences were granted, a DTI official suggested that
they should be sent with a covering letter to Herbert Smith pointing out
that the department had relied heavily on the legal firm's assurances. 'This
may give them (Herbert Smith) an incentive to let us know quickly if they
find in the future that they have been hoodwinked.' As neat a piece of back
covering as you could imagine.
In the words of the prosecuting counsel at the trial, Clowes ' was helped by
the reactions of those who strayed dangerously near to discovering the
truth. There seems to have been a reluctance in some of them to believe that
a fraud of this nature and scale could have been perpetrated.'
There are obvious parallels here with the Robert Maxwell affair, both in the
City's willing suspension of disbelief and in the character of the man and
his business. For Clowes, deception became a matter of routine. The process
was facilitated by a dense web of offshore companies and by the construction
of a financial control system which only he could fully understand.
The one thing that really mattered was that more money should be coming in
than was flowing out in repayments to investors. That way there would be no
awkward complaints from the public, and there would be enough left over for
all the trappings of tycoonery. There were the yachts, the private jets, and
the imaginative extravagances. On one private jet trip to Jersey costing
thousands, Mrs Clowes wrote a single word on the disembarkation card to
describe the purpose of her visit: 'lunch'.
There are familiar lessons to be drawn from all this. As Lever says, no
system of investor protection can cater for people who succumb to promises
of excessively high rates of return. He quotes Professor Gower, the
architect of Britain's financial services legislation: 'Regulation should be
no greater than is necessary to protect reasonable people from being made
fools of.'
For those who were prepared to look, Barlow Clowes' schemes carried all the
well-known danger signals. There was the prominent use of the word
'guarantee' - a promise that should almost always make investors reach for
their revolvers, especially if it is made by a tinpot outfit with no record.
There were the high rates of return, and the lack of transparency. And yet,
right up to the very end, the money poured in.
Could it happen again? Lever's verdict is that the Financial Services Act,
which came into effect too late to nip Barlow Clowes in the bud, will make
it harder in future for frauds to cheat the public systematically on a large
scale. If they do, they will be caught sooner under the new system than
under the old. But sooner, he warns, could still mean a period of years.
It is true that one of the very first acts of the newly-formed Securities
and Investments Board was to grasp the nettle which other supervisors had
been avoiding for years: in May 1988, it closed Barlow Clowes. But Britain's
regulatory structure remains fragmented, with responsibilities shared
between the Bank of England and a range of self-regulatory organisations.
The story of confusion and buck passing told in The Barlow Clowes Affair
will strengthen the hand of those who argue that the UK's system of
financial regulation needs to be made still less complex in structure and
more pro-active in style.
Lever claims that Barlow Clowes was the largest financial scandal of the
century. But he is already out of date - and the fact is that the current
title holder, the Maxwell disaster, took place largely under the auspices of
the new City regulators.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
