<HEADLINE>
FT  23 MAR 92 / A price-tag on the promises: Martin Wolf examines the
Conservative party's criticism of Labour's hidden agenda for increased
public spending
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARTIN WOLF
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LAST WEEK saw the battle of the two main parties' plans for taxation. On
Saturday, the Conservative party shifted its focus towards Labour's plans
for public spending. Labour's manifesto, it claimed, has 37 policy pledges
that would cost an extra Pounds 37.9bn annually by the last year of a full
parliament, in current prices.
These charges and counter-charges are at the heart of the election campaign.
The Conservative party seems to have abandoned hope of convincing the voters
that a fourth term would do them much good. Instead, it seeks to frighten
them about Labour's harmful intentions. So is John Smith the sober and
responsible chancellor-in-waiting that he appears to be? Or is he, as the
Conservatives argue, the respectable face of the spendthrift socialist
tiger?
Whatever the truth, Mr Smith has been winning the battle of appearances. In
his shadow budget, presented last week, he promised to raise additional net
revenue of Pounds 3.3bn in 1992-93 (half a percentage point of gross
domestic product) and Pounds 6.8bn in 1993-94 (one percentage point of GDP),
by comparison with the budget presented by Norman Lamont. The Conservatives
wished to make these proposals appear threatening to a substantial
proportion of the electorate. They have failed.
As the Institute of Fiscal Studies has pointed out, 48 per cent of the
population would be better off under the Labour budget than under that of
the Conservatives, 35 per cent would be in roughly the same position, while
only 17 per cent would be better off under the Conservatives. The majority
of the electorate would, therefore, either be unaffected by these proposals
or - especially if they were on below average incomes and were either
pensioners or parents - would benefit substantially.
The Labour budget may be harshly criticised for the shock it would impose on
the higher paid and for its longer term effect on incentives. But since each
adult has one vote in an election, it looks politically invulnerable. The
more Conservatives focus their attack on Mr Smith's shadow budget, the more
a majority of voters is likely to appreciate the transfers proposed.
The Conservatives need a knock-out punch. The campaign against Labour's
wider spending plans is to be that punch. The items they enumerate in
support of their case against Labour profligacy include commitments to:
increased basic pensions, costed at Pounds 2,700m;
equalisation of pension age at 60, costed at Pounds 3,000m;
uprating of pensions in line with earnings, costed at Pounds 2,100m;
improved and extended invalid allowances, costed at Pounds 2,140m;
disability benefits, costed at Pounds 1,300m;
increased child benefit, costed at Pounds 730m;
increased spending on National Health Service, costed at Pounds 3,000m;
increased investment in housing, costed at Pounds 3,000m;
a high-speed rail network linking every region to the Channel Tunnel, costed
at Pounds 3,000m;
improved public transport for London, costed at Pounds 550m;
increase in share of GDP spent on education to 1979 level, costed at Pounds
2,600m;
reaching the aid target of 0.7 per cent of GDP, costed at Pounds 2,500m;
increased powers for local authorities, costed at Pounds 3,000m;
implementation of the European Social Charter, costed at Pounds 600m; and
improved public sector pay and conditions, and introduction of a statutory
minimum wage, costed at Pounds 3,600m.
To this lengthy list, the Conservatives add another 22 items, costed at
Pounds 4,075m, ranging all the way from improved legal aid (Pounds 115m), to
increased spending on training (Pounds 200m), via free eye tests (Pounds
165m) and funeral payments (Pounds 80m).
Yet what Mr Smith has definitively proposed would be an increase in public
spending of only Pounds 6.8bn in 1993-94. Specified items would be the
increase in the weekly state retirement pension by Pounds 5 for a single
person and Pounds 8 for a couple, costing Pounds 2.3bn in a full year, and
the increase in child benefit to Pounds 9.95 for all children, costing
Pounds 750m in a full year. The Pounds 3.5bn left over from the shadow
chancellor's proposed increase in net taxation would then go on health,
education 'and other vital public services'.
Included in Mr Smith's sums are immediate implementation of a Pounds 1.1bn
'Recovery Programme', embracing:
enhanced first year capital allowances in manufacturing;
measures to help small business;
a new skills fund and restoration of cuts in Employment Training and Youth
Training;
a job experience programme for the unemployed;
phased release of capital receipts held by local authorities from the sale
of council houses; and
a pilot leasing programme for British Rail.
How plausible, against this, is the Conservative complaint of a
not-so-hidden Labour party spending agenda? That Labour has intentions in
all the areas listed by the Conservatives - some more, some less specific -
is clear. But many of the costings must be doubted. Would increased powers
for local authorities, for example, really cost Pounds 3bn? Would improved
public sector pay and the implementation of the national minimum wage cost
Pounds 3.6bn? Would a high speed rail link to the Channel Tunnel cost Pounds
3bn in a single year in the life of the next parliament? None of these
numbers looks compelling.
Nevertheless, Conservative charges cannot be ignored. Labour has many
commitments in its programme and they will cost money. Where might it come
from? Could Labour rely on the 'growth dividend' to fund substantial further
increases in public spending? The plausible answer is 'no'. If Mr Smith goes
to the Treasury cupboard, he is likely to find that it is already bare.
The charts give the background, including forecasts based on the Financial
Statement and Budget Report of 1992-93. The government's forecasts imply an
increase in the share of non-north sea taxation in GDP, as the recovery
takes hold. The current rise in public spending as a share of GDP is
explained in large measure by the recession, as was the case in the
mid-1970s and early 1980s. Nevertheless, the share of public spending in GDP
would remain below levels reached between 1973-74 and 1986-87. The ratio is
also expected to fall after 1993-94, but the public sector borrowing
requirement will still not go below 3 per cent of GDP, the benchmark level
agreed at Maastrich for the path to economic and monetary union, before
1995-96.
What then might be the effect of a Labour government? Suppose, first, that
Labour only increased public spending and taxation by the amounts already
announced, plus the notional tax reductions pencilled in by the government
for 1995-96 and 1996-97. The result, as shown. would be only modestly above
the government's forecasts.
Suppose, second, that the Conservatives were right about Labour's agenda. On
the Treasury's assumption about economic growth, public spending would rise
to at least 46 per cent of GDP. This is, it should be noted, no implausible
figure. The burden would then still be lower than in both the mid-1970s and
the early 1980s. But it would be at least 6 percentage points higher than
the Conservatives forecast, possibly optimistically, for themselves.
Nothing suggests that recovery would be faster under Labour than the
Conservatives. Neither is the economy likely to do better than the Treasury
now forecasts: economic growth at an average of 3 per cent a year between
1991-92 and 1996-97 period. This is as fast as the recovery from the last
recession, even though there is to be no sterling devaluation this time,
while real interest rates are high and the personal sector remains highly
indebted.
Even with such a recovery, public spending at 46 per cent of GDP by 1996-97
would not prove consistent with the Maastricht target, which is for a public
deficit of 3 per cent of GDP in a normal year, absent tax increases. Without
the government's proposed tax cuts in 1995-96 and 1996-97, but with Mr
Smith's proposed tax increases, general government receipts would be about
40 1/2 per cent of GDP in 1996-97, on the Treasury assumptions for economic
growth. This would imply an overall deficit - under full implementation of
Labour promises, as costed by the Conservatives - of 5-6 per cent of GDP.
To reduce that deficit to the target of 3 per cent of GDP would require not
the tax increases that the Conservative are suggesting, but perhaps half
that amount. The reason for the difference is that the Conservatives say
they want to lower the borrowing requirement to  3/4 per cent of GDP by
1996-97, while Labour might stick to the Maastricht 3 per cent.
Nevertheless, even with the hoped for recovery, Labour could not implement
all its dreams without extra taxation of perhaps 2-3 per cent of GDP,
equivalent to 6p on the basic rate of tax.
Yet this is far from the worst possibility. What would happen if real
economic growth were to average only 2 per cent over the next five years,
not 3 per cent? Other things equal, revenue in 1996-97 might then be more
than Pounds 15bn less than is now forecast by the Treasury for that year.
Even ignoring the effects of lower growth on public spending itself, that
would mean a PSBR at about 3 per cent of GDP. For a Labour party trying to
meet all of its aspirations, the deficit might be 7-8 per cent of GDP.
Underneath the smoke is a genuine battle. On plausible assumptions, the
growth dividend may have already been fully spoken for by the government. If
growth does not pick up as hoped, it may be impossible to enjoy increases in
government spending above those already planned, without breaching the limit
agreed at Maastricht. Even if growth were to be as fast as hoped, Labour
might still have to choose between all the spending it desires and higher
taxes.
If Labour were determined to spend substantially more in real terms than it
has already announced in its shadow budget, further tax increases do,
indeed, look likely. Alternatively, Labour supporters will end up
discontented. Conservative charges may be wildly aimed, but they are not
entirely off the mark.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 16
</PAGE>
