<HEADLINE>
FT  23 MAR 92 / Engineers are urged to declare 'war on wear'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW BAXTER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A NATIONAL campaign being launched today is intended to save British
manufacturing industry Pounds 1.5bn a year by encouraging greater awareness
of one of engineering's more arcane 'ologies' - tribology, which is the
study of friction, lubrication and wear.
The Tribology Action Campaign, which comes with a self-help support package,
telephone helpline and regional workshops aims to declare 'war on wear' and
promote the application of the science across all areas of design,
production and operation.
The campaign, organised by the Institution of Mechanical Engineers, is
supported by the Department of Trade and Industry and sponsored by companies
ranging from British Coal to RHP Bearings and Silkolene Lubricants.
The aim is to reduce wear and tear in machinery through greater control of
friction. The projected annual savings of Pounds 1.5bn come from improved
efficiency through reduced energy, labour, maintenance and machinery costs.
The Institution of Mechanical Engineers said additional benefits included
reduced pollution and the potential to cut industrial energy consumption by
up to 10 per cent a year.
Mr Brian Halligan, campaign chairman and a member of the council of the
institution, said research commissioned by the organisation showed 75 per
cent of UK industry threw 'money down the drain' through lack of awareness.
He added: 'UK industry spends Pounds 8bn a year on maintaining direct
production assets. Yet, at any one time, 50 per cent of its machines are in
need of attention.'
</TEXT>
