<HEADLINE>
FT  23 MAR 92 / City firms 'unprepared for fire and bomb alerts'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
AN ESTIMATE of the time lost to financial institutions in the City through
such interruptions as security alerts, fires, floods and power failure has
been issued by Telehouse, managers of a building in Docklands designed to
withstand failures of facilities, Andrew Jack writes.
It shows that more than a quarter of the 71 institutions questioned had
suffered interruptions to dealing lasting at least an hour in the past year.
At least 15 per cent of those questioned said they had no contingency plans
to deal with interruptions caused by alerts, and a further 49 per cent
taking part in the survey appeared to have no other adequate mechanisms to
deal with a dealing-room failure.
Mr Nick Simms, marketing manager of Telehouse, said a further informal study
of companies in the Broadgate area of the City showed that at least 7 banks
had lost three hours of trading time following a bomb scare earlier this
month.
