<HEADLINE>
FT  23 MAR 92 / Secretaries 'often used as glorified typists'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DIANE SUMMERS, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MANY secretaries feel trapped in their jobs and are still treated as
glorified typists in spite of their 'amazing mix of skills,' according to
the Industrial Society.
Managers were wasting their companies' money by failing to delegate properly
to their secretaries, the society, an independent organisation that promotes
good industrial relations, said before publishing a survey of more than 500
secretaries and 300 managers.
According to the survey more than 40 per cent of bosses see typing as the
first priority in a secretary's job. The society commented that the
difference between a typist and a secretary needed to be defined in many
organisations. This would help to 'eliminate the frustrations caused by
under-use' of secretaries' abilities and training. Companies could also save
money by employing typists instead of secretaries to process text.
The survey indicates that a boss's ideal secretary shows initiative and is
accurate, but is not assertive and probably does not display a sense of
humour.
Asked which attributes they rated most in secretaries, managers put
initiative top, followed by accuracy and confidentiality. Low ratings were
received for flexibility, confidence, knowledge and tact. Bottom of the list
of desired qualities came a sense of humour and assertiveness.
The society said it was difficult to see how a secretary could show
initiative without having knowledge. Furthermore, confidence was essential
if secretaries were to do many of the jobs bosses wanted.
The jobs secretaries perform have changed significantly since 1987, when the
society last carried out a similar survey. Today's secretaries are likely to
spend less time arranging travel and meetings.
Secretaries. Industrial Society, 3 Carlton House Terrace, London SW1Y 5DG.
Pounds 15.
</TEXT>
