FT  23 MAR 92 / Punjab calls in army to curb killings
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
PUNJAB'S newly elected chief minister yesterday called in the Indian army to
help police crush Sikh militants who have shot dead almost 70 people in
recent days, Reuter reports.
Mr Beant Singh said two army generals and Punjab's police chief would
oversee the crackdown in the industrial city of Ludhiana and areas south of
it. Soldiers and paramilitaries are backing up police in house-to-house
searches.
Sikh militants, who are fighting for a separate homeland, have vowed to
punish anyone who voted in the February 19 elections or who collaborates
with Mr Singh's government.
