<HEADLINE>
FT  23 MAR 92 / Kinnock says Labour is 'party of industry'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVO DAWNAY and RALPH ATKINS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR NEIL KINNOCK set out Labour's agenda for the start of the second week of
election campaigning yesterday with a 'charm offensive' squarely targeted at
industry and commerce.
In a question and answer session with Labour-supporting business leaders at
London's Hilton Hotel, he said a Labour government would 'enable' business
but not interfere in it.
His business 'brunch' was hosted by Lord Hollick, managing director of MAI,
the financial services group, and also addressed by Mr Gordon Brown, the
shadow trade secretary. It was clearly aimed at portraying Labour as having
adopted the best practices of governments of all political colours in the
European Community.
However, amid a barrage of Tory attacks, Mr John Smith, the shadow
chancellor, had to correct comments by Mr Roy Hattersley, Labour's deputy
leader. On TV-am Mr Hattersley said an increase in Labour's proposed 50 per
cent top rate of income tax could not be ruled out. Mr Smith said the rate
would not rise above 50 per cent but failed to stem charges from
Conservative frontbenchers that Mr Hattersley had revealed a hidden agenda
of new tax rises.
Mr Michael Heseltine, environment secretary, said the 'gaffe' had 'confirmed
what we suspected all along - that Labour are secretly planning to put up
taxes way beyond the levels they have admitted'.
Mr Kinnock's central theme - that Labour is now 'the party of industry' -
will be further developed at today's launch of the party's manufacturing
policy in the West Midlands.
Party strategists said they would build on Mr Kinnock's 'prime ministerial'
image and Labour's positive agenda, contrasting it with a Tory campaign
which, they said, had increasingly become negative attacks.
Opinion poll showing 'steady, inexorable movement' in Labour's favour had
panicked the Tories into deploying Mrs Margaret Thatcher to give 'backbone'
to a lacklustre campaign, Mr Kinnock said.
Looking confident and relaxed, he used yesterday's meeting to appeal for
business' support. He argued that, of all the EC governments, Britain's was
unique in believing 'the function of the state was to withdraw from all
responsibility' for business. Labour believed that government 'does have a
real role' in aiding the development of the economy and the manufacturing
base.
Asked by one businessman how nervous voters might be persuaded that Labour
would not adopt more radical policies once elected, Mr Kinnock said such a
move would be an exercise in suicidal 'throat slitting'.
Labour's goal was not merely to achieve office but to stay in office, he
said.
Labour's business brunch was attended by a 100-strong audience that included
Mr Denny Bernstein of Monarch Airlines, Ms Carmen Callil of Chatto and
Windus, Mr David Goldstone of Regalian Properties, Mr Paul Loach of
Framlington plc, Mr Michael Montague of Williams Holdings, Mr Brian Oakley
of Logica Cambridge, Mr Swraj Paul of Caparo Industries and Sir Sidney
Sternberg of Martin Slowe Estates.
Mr Smith later made clear that a Labour government would not set zero
inflation as its target, but would be content with a rate equal to the EC
average.
</TEXT>
