FT  23 MAR 92 / Albanians return to the polls
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TIRANA
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
After a year of multi-party democracy, Albanians returned to the polls
yesterday for an election that could break the former communists' grip on
power, Reuter reports from Tirana.
'This day marks the end of communism and the beginning of democracy in
Albania,' said opposition leader Sali Berisha, whose inexperienced
Democratic party was trounced by the former communists in last year's polls.
Turnout was high in the capital, Tirana. But many voters delayed their
arrival at polling stations until they had queued for bread dis-tributed by
the army - a daily necessity in the chaos that followed last year's poll.
No big disturbances were reported.
The elections, in which more than 500 candidates were fighting for places in
a new 140-seat assembly, caps a year of political and social turmoil as
Europe's poorest state tries to cope with the birth-pains of democracy.
Results are expected today.
The Democratic party said one entire set of ballot slips had been stolen
from a southern village and incomplete electoral lists were causing delays
and confusion elsewhere.
