<HEADLINE>
FT  21 MAR 92 / World Stock Markets (America): Dow edges higher in heavy
early volume
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NIKKI TAIT
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Wall Street
WITH a 'triple witching' hanging over the US stockmarket yesterday, share
prices edged slightly higher during most of the trading session, before
jumping sharply in the final half-hour, writes Nikki Tait in New York.
The upward trend persisted throughout most of the day, the market's only
modest retreat coming in a brief period after lunch. Volumes were moderately
heavy for the day although dealers suggested that a burst of business
occured when the market opened and again in the final hour's trading. Many
investors were expected to remain on the sidelines until the potentially
volatile session was over.
By the 4pm close, the Dow Jones Industrial Average was up 14.99 points on
the previous night's close, at 3276.39. The more broadly-based Standard &amp;
Poor's 500 Index gained 1.45 points to 411.25.
However, the Nasdaq index, which measures the over-the-counter market, eased
by 1.68 points to 624.28.
On the New York Stock Exchange, advancing stocks outpaced declining ones by
a margin of approximately three to two on volume of 246.7m shares.
AT&amp;T, the large US telecommunications group, was among the most active
shares traded during the morning session. They gained  3/4 to Dollars 40 5/8
, on confirmation of a Dollars 1.4bn contract from the US Internal Revenue
Service for computer equipment and services. The contract was awarded to the
company in July, but the decision ran into controversy.
Also rising sharply were shares in Allied Signal, up Dollars 2 7/8 to
Dollars 52 1/4 . The company said it expected first quarter earnings of 85
cents a share, some 15 to 20 cents higher than analysts' had been
predicting.
Allied Signal said reasons for the better-than-expected figures lay partly
in an accelerated restructuring programme, and partly in relatively strong
sales in the automotive aftermarket. It did warn, however, that it was too
early to say whether this would be maintained throughout 1992.
A couple of US car companies enjoyed useful gains in the morning, shares in
Ford gaining  3/8 to Dollars 40 1/2 and General Motors rising  3/4 to
Dollars 39 1/8 . Only Chrysler, weakest of the 'Big Three' Detroit
manufacturers, eased back - by  1/2 to Dollars 17 7/8 . Analysts at
Painewebber, the Wall Street brokerage, were said to have raised their
earnings estimates for the industry.
Canada
TORONTO SHARE prices strayed little from yesterday"s close, leaving the
index with a slight loss on the week.
The composite index edged up 3.22 points to close at 3,469.95, off 5.84
points on the week. Volume was 29.97m shares against 28.138m the day before.
The transportation sub-group led the gainers with a 1.20 per cent climb on
index, and financial services, mining and industrial products posted smaller
gains. Energy and consumer products were off moderately.
PWA Corp, the day's most active issue, rallied 0.30 to 5 1/4 on PWA's
announcement that it was discussing a strategic partnership with American
Airlines.
</TEXT>
