<HEADLINE>
FT  21 MAR 92 / Learning how to mix it
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The faltering start to Mr John Major's campaign was accidentally highlighted
in a comment after his unusually aggressive speech at the rally in
Manchester on Thursday night. According to an aide, the prime minister said
it was the first time in 16 months that he had said what he felt.
Quite apart from the admission that he had not really hit his stride until
some days into the campaign, the comment points to a fundamental change of
strategy.
An earlier plan was for Mr Major to be above the political fray in a
statesmanlike fashion, leaving the negative campaigning on Labour to those
without quite such nice smiles.
But the speech on Thursday showed that Mr Major is prepared to mix it with
the opposition.
His speech did indeed, as he was at pains to point out, cover education,
housing and the Citizen's Charter.
It dealt more passionately - and to more applause - with Labour's tax plans,
the last Labour government's continuation of a 'forelock society', and the
unfitness of Labour to govern because of its stand on defence and,
implicitly, the putative hot-headedness of its leader.
The speech acquired lift-off with Mr Major's delivery. This was enlivened by
his encounter with a jostling group of demonstrators as he tried to do a
walkabout in Bolton on Thursday afternoon. He abandoned his usual monochrome
style for a note of passion, and his normal bureaucratic turn of phrase to
denounce 'the ugly face of Labour that I hate'.
There is a clear downside to television pictures showing a leader being the
focus of a hostile protest. For someone against whom one of the main charges
is blandness, there is a brighter side as well.
And the Tory tour party is in the business of being positive, after a week
which began flatly, as the economic output figures hijacked Tuesday's
campaigning, and unemployment dominated much of Thursday's.
Among the hopeful signs is the belief that the worst of the economic
indicators have already come out.
Most hopes are pinned on the new 'bite' in Mr Major's setpiece campaigning.
The prime minister still seems nice rather than Churchillian to the few
innocent bystanders he meets on tour, but he has at least shown that being
pleasant is not incompatible with behaving and sounding as though he really
does not want Labour to win.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
