<HEADLINE>
FT  21 MAR 92 / Election 1992: Labour tax plans 'compete with EC'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EDWARD BALLS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE STATISTICAL battle over rival tax regimes rests on complex and highly
contentious foundations.
Comparisons of international tax systems, and even of the British fiscal
regime at different points in history, involve assumptions about individual
and family circumstances.
The UK tax system looks simple when compared with the complicated structure
of tax and social-security contributions in France and Germany. Moreover,
internationally comparable and up-to-date figures on incomes earned or taxes
paid are hard to find.
The chart alongside is based on statistics from the Organisation for
Economic Co-operation and Development and FT calculations about the effects
of Labour's shadow Budget. The figures in the lower chart are based on the
marginal tax and social security liabilities of a single person in France,
Germany and the UK.
Labour's plan to increase marginal tax rates for high income earners would
still leave most single British tax-payers facing lower marginal tax rates
than in either Germany or France. However, under the Conservatives, the top
rate tax-payers will face substantially lower marginal tax rates than in
Britain's main European competitors.
These comparisons ignore the complications introduced by married couple and
child tax allowances. The combination of these allowances would reduce the
marginal tax rate faced by families in France and Germany compared to those
shown here.
Marginal tax rates, the amount of tax paid on each additional slice of
income earned, are usually plotted against money income. A better way to
make international comparisons of the tax burden is to show the marginal tax
rate facing each income decile from the poorest 10 per cent to the highest
10 per cent.
The top 50 per cent of single French tax-payers all currently face a higher
marginal tax rate than would confront upper income earners under Labour's
plans. Only the top 20 per cent of British tax-payers would face a higher
marginal rate than the same group in Germany under Labour's plans.
Labour's tax plans, the Tories argue, will heap a heavy proportion of the
tax burden on middle and upper income tax payers. Nearly all of the top 50
per cent of wage earners will face a higher marginal rate than at present.
Yet most single French and German upper income earners, and almost all lower
income earners in these countries, face higher marginal tax rates than would
be the case under either a Labour or a Conservative government.
The remaining charts provide a historical perspective on the current debate.
The UK, compared to France and Germany, has been relatively lightly taxed
throughout the 1980s. The total UK tax burden as a percentage of GDP was 40
per cent in 1990, marginally higher than in 1980 - the Tories' first full
year in office.
For much of the 1980s the personal income tax burden was more evenly shared
in the UK than elsewhere in Europe. In 1987, the richest 10 per cent of UK
households paid 43.4 per cent of total direct taxation comparted to 53 per
cent in Germany and 60 per cent in France.
It is clear from all these calculations that they do not support simple
political claims from either side. That is unlikely to prevent the
politicians using them in a debate which will probably remain at the centre
of the election campaign
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 7
