<HEADLINE>
FT  21 MAR 92 / Election 1992: Ashdown barracked by Militant
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RALPH ATKINS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR PADDY ASHDOWN, Liber-al Democrat leader, was jostled and barracked
yesterday by Militant sympathisers supporting Mr Terry Fields, who was
expelled from the Labour party but is defending Liverpool Broadgreen as an
independent.
Mr Ashdown - who was campaigning on housing policy in Liverpool - challenged
Mr Neil Kinnock, the Labour leader, to confront Militant.
Continuing the hectic pace he has set himself, Mr Ashdown said that bad
housing was a cost of the government's anti-inflation strategy.
'Anybody can bring inflation down by stopping the economy dead in its
tracks,' he said.
He called for councils' capital receipts to be freed in order to kickstart
the construction industry.
Mr Ashdown, who is thankful that his party has not been squeezed by Labour
or the Tories in the first week of the campaign, also called for an
independent central bank and for sterling to be moved to the narrow band of
the exchange rate mechanism of the European Monetary System in order to bear
down on inflation.
Later, at his official adoption meeting in his Yeovil constituency, Mr
Ashdown complained of the 'arrogance' of the Labour and Tory parties 'who
have spent these last weeks and months of their campaign not debating about
the future, but arguing about the past'.
He added: 'The Liberal Democrats are the only party in the election which
has recognised the seriousness of Britain's current situation. There is a
real danger that, under either of the two other parties, that situation
could well become catastrophic.'
</TEXT>
