<HEADLINE>
FT  21 MAR 92 / Yugoslav foes become brothers in arms sales
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LAURA SILBER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BELGRADE
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE Serb-controlled Yugoslav army and the republic of Croatia, until
recently at war, have joined forces to produce weapons for export, writes
Laura Silber in Belgrade.
Djuro Djakovic, a weapons factory in Croatia, will honour a Dollars 300m
two-year contract for delivery of 200 M-84 tanks to Kuwait. The Yugoslav
federal office which oversees arms sales said the outbreak of war had
prevented Yugoslavia from fulfilling the contract.
Croatia will get Dollars 300,000 of the Dollars 1.5m price of each tank.
Factories from all Yugoslav republics contribute parts for the M-84s.
General Antun Tus, chief of staff of Croat forces, admitted it may 'sound
paradoxical that warring countries are in this joint business of production
and export of weapons to a third country'. But he insisted there was no
danger because the tanks were entirely under Croatian control.
</TEXT>
