<HEADLINE>
FT  21 MAR 92 / Ukraine in bitter attack on Moscow
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRYSTIA FREELAND, JOHN LLOYD and ANDREW HILL
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   KIEV, BRUSSELS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE SHARPENING tension between Russia and Ukraine burst into the open last
night at the end of a meeting in Kiev of the leaders of the Commonwealth of
Independent States (CIS).
President Leonid Kravchuk of Ukraine, the summit's host, was openly and
bitterly caustic towards Mr Boris Yeltsin, the Russian president, before
hundreds of journalists at a final press conference.
Declaring none of the 23 agreements signed had any real importance and
Ukraine had signed only one minor technical document among the military
treaties, Mr Kravchuk said while he held the Russian people in high esteem,
'I forbear from commenting on Russian leaders.'
Accusing Mr Yeltsin of being ironic in speaking earlier of a 'constructive
attitude' at the summit, Mr Kravchuk matched his irony by saying Russia's
attitude had pleased him, 'because I now understand we will never agree to a
division of the assets of the former Soviet Union.'
At the summit Mr Yeltsin brusquely dismissed Ukraine's proposal to discuss
splitting up all former Soviet property, including foreign embassies and
reserves of the former Soviet state bank, Gosbank.
In contrast to bland statements by Mr Yeltsin and other presidents that the
CIS was essential and vigorously alive, Mr Kravchuk said: 'If the situation
does not improve, the commonwealth is doomed.' Later, senior Ukrainian
officials said they believed the next scheduled CIS session in Tashkent
would be its last.
Mr Kravchuk as good as called his Russian counterpart a liar. He said he had
not phoned Mr Yeltsin earlier this week to promise to return tactical
nuclear missiles, as the Russian leader claimed - and, turning to Mr Yeltsin
on the podium at the press conference, he said: 'Boris Nikolaevich (Yeltsin)
can confirm that.' Mr Yeltsin made no response.
Earlier, Mr Kravchuk confirmed that Ukraine had ceased to send tactical
nuclear missiles to Russia. No more would be sent until guarantees had been
given that they would be destroyed under international supervision.
Western military and diplomatic observers at the meeting said Mr Kravchuk's
call for international supervision might strike a sympathetic chord in the
west, which is concerned about proliferation of nuclear states.
Ominously, the Ukrainian president said Russia could not be blamed for
acting according to its own interests - and 'we must learn to do the same,
we must act in the interests of our people and will not be swayed from
this.'
The one positive agreement appeared to be a resolution to create a CIS
peacekeeping force for use in national and ethnic conflicts, as in the
disputed territory of Nagorno-Karabakh and the Trans Dnestr region of
Moldova.
Mr Seitkazy Mataev, spokesman for President Nursultan Nazarbayev of
Kazakhastan, said that after an hour of 'heated discussions' the presidents
had agreed to create a force that would intervene once there was a ceasefire
and on the invitation of at least one side. But the force would have no
military role.
Ukraine and Russia now seem set for a further dangerous escalation of
tension, with none of the outstanding disagreements between them - over
splitting up property, maintenance of borders and division of the Black Sea
Fleet - even discussed, let alone settled.
About 33,000 St Petersburg students and a large number of pensioners will
each get Rbs150 out of funds from the sale of EC food delivered to the city,
writes Andrew Hill in Brussels. The European Commission said about Ecu80m
(Pounds 57m) of nearly Ecu200m of food aid to St Petersburg and Moscow had
been delivered.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
